<HEAD>Orioles Snap Losing Streak at 21</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> snapped their record-breaking losing streak at 21 games Friday night, beating the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> 9-0 for their first win of the season. The <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> did it in style, allowing only four hits and letting only one runner get past first base. Three cases of champagne were on ice and waiting for the <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> in their clubhouse afterward, the reward for the worst start in major league history. <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> established the longest losing streak in American League history with Thursday's defeat in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. They stopped short of the major league mark of 23 consecutive losses by the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phillies </ORGANIZATION> in 1961. The old record for the worst start in major league history was held by both the 1904 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Senators and the 1920 <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>, who lost their first 13 games. A crowd of 14,059 sat quietly in 56-degree temperature as <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> stopped its march of misery.
