<SECOND>PM-Tickets,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Wins Ticket Battle, But War Could Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT KISCO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Helga </PERSON> <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON> is 83 years old, does n't do a lot of driving and gets very few parking tickets. Well, she gets a lot of tickets, actually, but she should n't. Mrs. <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, had a license plate stolen from her 1975 <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Duster </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> two years ago. By the end of the next day, she had reported the theft to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police and received new plates from the Department of Motor Vehicles. That was not the end of it. Mrs. <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON> has gotten notices from the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Violations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> about 169 unpaid tickets totaling $ 9,299, including interest and penalties. She tried to explain, but the notices kept coming. A default judgment had been issued, they said. We can take your property and bank accounts, they said. `` I was living in a nightmare,'' she said. Finally through the help of state Sen. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodhue </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON> was given a letter here on Thursday from the parking bureau clearing her of the tickets and saying she did n't owe <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> a cent _ for now. `` We solved this, but there is something wrong with the system,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Goodhue </PERSON> said Thursday. She and <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Breen </PERSON>, an administrative supervisor for the <ORGANIZATION> PVB </ORGANIZATION> said that as long as someone is still out there with her license plate, the computers say it's her car violating the parking laws And she'll still get dunning notices. `` There is nothing in the system to trip it if someone has reported the car stolen or the plates stolen,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Goodhue </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON> had so much trouble because she had lost the police receipt showing she had reported her car stolen. That infuriates Mrs. <PERSON> Goodhue </PERSON>. `` There should be a system to double check against stolen license plates and stolen cars,'' she said. `` You can have two cars out there with the same plate and the wrong person getting dunned. These things should n't be allowed to continue happening. PVB computers should talk to DMV computers.'' <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> admitted that there was no mechanical system that would notify PVB that a ticket was given to a stolen car or plate. The burden of proof was on the victim, as it were, to show that the vehicle on the ticket is n't theirs or was n't where the ticket said it was, he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Huitt </PERSON>, now driving a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escort </ORGANIZATION>, says she will frame her `` $ 10,000 letter.'' <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said she should also hope police find the car with her license plate and destroy that plate so her nightmare can end for good.
