<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-HolyCity     04-29 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Holy City,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jews, Arabs Vow Never To Leave Holy Ancient City</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinian Moslems respond to a prayer call from a minaret and head for a mosque in the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. A few hundred yards away, ultra-Orthodox Jews dressed in black bow again and again before a stone wall. Arabs and Israelis, enemies but neighbors inside the walls of ancient <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, pass without speaking. Israeli riot police stand guard on rooftops and in alleys, where anti-Israeli graffiti are scrawled on some walls. <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is a city both Jews and Moslem passionately claim _ and, reluctantly, share. For the Jews, it is, as the Old Testament's Psalms say, `` <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, my highest joy.'' For the Moslems, it is `` Al Quds,'' or `` The Holy.'' Its name means `` city of peace,'' but it is at the heart of the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. If Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is able to persuade the two sides to sit at a negotiating table, the issue of this city's future is likely to be a major stumbling block Initially settled about 2,500 years before the birth of Christ, <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> has been beseiged and conquered 37 times by foreign forces, including the Romans, the Crusaders and the Arab general <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON>. Today, walled ancient <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> covers a crowded square mile of narrow cobblestone streets, broad courtyards hidden behind locked doors, and a colorful Arab market often shuttered by strikes in the 5-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule. Nowhere in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> are Jewish-Arab differences more strongly felt than in the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Hundreds of Palestinian worshipers and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops converge each Friday for Moslem prayers at the city's two holiest mosques, the Dome of the Rock and <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqsa </PERSON>, where angry Arab protests often erupt. Tear gas thrown to quell the demonstrations sometimes disturbs Jewish prayers at the adjoining Western Wall, the last remnant of the second Jewish temple destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70 and <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>'s holiest shrine. It is here that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seeks to break the back of the uprising by forcing merchants who supply the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> to obey Israeli rule instead of <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> orders. Fourteen Arab merchants face up to two years in jail for opening shops during PLO-ordained hours in violation of army orders. As the city grows increasingly tense, however, most of the 17,000 Moslems and 2,000 Jews who live inside ancient <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> say they grow more determined in their commitment to stay. `` The <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> tastes of history. In every stone there is a book,'' said Palestinian poet <PERSON> Fawzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakri </PERSON>, born within <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s walls 42 years ago `` I do n't live in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> _ it lives in me,'' he said. `` I can never leave.'' For Israeli <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who has lived here five years, the soul of the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is in its Western Wall, also known as the Wailing Wall. `` The wall offers solace to so many Jewish people. You see them day after day, talking to God,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, 44, a native of <LOCATION> Greenbelt </LOCATION>, Md. `` But the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is more than a shrine. It is my home,'' she said. `` If I am threatened, I will turn into a she-bear.'' The <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> was held by <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> for the first 19 years of Israeli history, until Jewish troops overran it in the 1967 war. Then <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> proclaimed the city its capital, a decision that Arabs refuse to recognize. Palestinians in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> still recall <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s conquest with bitterness. <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sneineh </PERSON>, 52, said he was forced to leave his apartment after the war when Israelis bought the building where he lived. He moved to <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> but was soon drawn back to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, even though he could afford only two rooms for his family of six. `` Nothing can match the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We will stay here and die here, which will surely happen because blood will be shed over this city.'' Israeli poet <PERSON> Yehuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Amichai </PERSON> sees the problem in dark terms. In his book `` Poems of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>,'' he writes: `` <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> stone is the only stone that can Feel pain. It has a network of nerves. From time to time <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> crowds into Mass protests like the tower of Babel. And afterward the city disperses, muttering Prayers of complaint and sporadic screams from churches And synagogues and loud-moaning mosques. Each to his own place.'' Palestinian poet <PERSON> Bakri </PERSON> knows <PERSON> Amichai </PERSON>'s poetry and appreciates that others love this city as he does. But he supports the Arab revolt. `` My only fear,'' <PERSON> Bakri </PERSON> said, fingering worry beads, `` is that the uprising brings this city closer to more calamity.''
