<SECOND>PM-Poland-Town,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Site Of Strike Was Built As Model Socialist Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The southern Polish mill town of <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> where thousands of steelworkers went on strike this week for higher pay was built in the 1950s to be a model socialist community. With a population of 220,000 people, <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> _ the name means <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mill </ORGANIZATION> _ dates from a Polish government resolution passed in 1949 by the communist government, then entering its Stalinist period. The government's aim was to build a huge steel plant next to the ancient Polish capital of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, then a stronghold of the Roman Catholic intelligentsia class that resisted the communist takeover of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Peasants from around <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> were brought to <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> with promises of a better life. They were to build the town and the steel plant and then work in the factory. The building of the town was celebrated in popular songs of the period and portrayed in many Polish films, including <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Wajda </PERSON>'s `` Man of Marble,'' about a model socialist worker who becomes disillusioned with the system. Today <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> is a drab working-class district which, like the rest of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, suffers from heavy pollution from the plant. The plant's 32,000 workers mostly live in the community. At first <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> was a separate town, but it was incorporated as <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s largest district in 1951. Besides the steel plant named after <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, the town features a huge monument to the first Soviet leader. The monument was damaged in a 1979 dynamite attack, but later was restored by authorities. Until 1977, the town had no church in keeping with its model-socialist image. But <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s then-archbishop, Cardinal <PERSON> Karol </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojtyla </PERSON>, now Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, worked relentlessly on government authorities for permission to build one. On May 15, 1977, he succeeded and consecrated the ultramodern Church of the Holy Ark, a local landmark and today one of at least five churches in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>.
