<SECOND>PM-Iran-War, Bjt,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Rethinks War Strategy After Double Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s twin defeats by the Iraqis on the <ORGANIZATION> Faw </ORGANIZATION> peninsula and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> have undermined its strategy that a war of attrition would eventually exhaust <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, military analysts say. `` Time is no longer on our side,'' <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s powerful <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaker and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, admitted in a <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> Radio interview last week `` That's very indicative that maybe the so-called pragmatists in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> are now going to get the upper hand. The Iranians have had a lot of sense knocked into them in the last few weeks,'' said <PERSON> Hans-Heino </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> specialist with the London-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s defeats on land and sea last week were their most serious in several years and analysts believe <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> needs a spectacular operation to regain the initiative in the 7 -LCB- - year-old gulf war <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Faw </ORGANIZATION> peninsula, captured by the Iranians in February 1986, was considered a `` strategic boon,'' but not vital. An <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> force led by units of the elite Presidential Guards seized the peninsula April 16-18. `` Its loss has had a major psychological impact,'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s loss of two frigates and a missile boat sunk or disabled by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on April 18 _ in the first serious clash between the <LOCATION> Iranians </LOCATION> and Americans _ is considered more important because those warships can not be replaced. Already, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s navy suffers a lack of spare parts and missiles, and most of its major surface ships, including two U.S.-built destroyers, are believed non-operational. `` The Iranians are having to rethink their whole strategy,'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` They've lost the initiative in many ways and they'll have to do something to get it back. The pressure is on them to pull off something spectacular.'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> and other Western analysts said an escalation in the Iraqis' use of outlawed chemical weapons in recent weeks and a seven-week missile bombardment of Iranian cities has also taken its toll on Iranian morale. A sustained bombing campaign by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s superior air force has damaged <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s already battered economy. Prime targets have been oil refineries and installations and power plants. Sources in the petroleum industry, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the bombing has cut <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s refining capacity by about a third. Oil exports, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s economic lifeblood, have been disrupted by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air raids on tankers in the gulf. A drop in demand for oil and increasingly shaky prices on the world market have eroded oil revenue on which the Iranians depend to pay for their war effort. The Middle East Economic Survey, a respected oil industry weekly newsletter published in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, reports that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has imported about 3 million barrels of refined petroleum products, such as kerosene and aviation gas, in recent weeks. `` This unprecedented sudden import of gas oil could be due to damage inflicted on Iranian refineries because of the war,'' the newsletter says. Diplomats recently in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> reported that almost two-thirds of the country's factories have been shut down by shortages of raw materials and spare parts. Others are operating at half their normal capacity or less. Only factories producing weapons, ammunition and other war-related items are working at full tilt, they said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is also increasingly isolated diplomatically. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s decision on Tuesday to sever its long-touchy relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, citing `` terrorism and subversion,'' was another blow. `` I'm sure other Arab states in the gulf will follow,'' <PERSON> Kopietz </PERSON> said. `` Despite the war, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> relies on countries like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> for trade and if that's affected it could have very serious repercussions.'' Since April 18, Iranian leaders, including <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, have been calling on their countrymen to mobilize, vowing revenge against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> states and `` reactionary states'' like <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. `` We are prepared to conduct military operations on several fronts,'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> declared. But the Iranians failed to launch their big winter offensive this year, triggering speculation that despite boasts of having trained 5 million men and women <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> is having recruiting problems. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>, the Marine officer who commands <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the region, testifed before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> recently that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was not capable of launching a major offensive in the foreseeable future because of manpower and materiel problems. Although the Iranians outnumber the Iraqis three-to-one in population, <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> said `` the fact is that the Iraqis right now have more men under arms than the Iranians do.'' But despite the problems, the analysts do not believe the Iranians are likely give up what Islamic patriarch <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> considers a crusade to crush his long-time adversary, President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.
