<FIRST>r a PM-High-TechCarts     04-29 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Tech Carts,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grocery Cart Enters The Video Age</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The grocery cart of the future is here _ a high-tech, video-equipped gadget that can say hello and offer games, shopping tips, sports scores and _ here's the catch _ on-the-spot advertising to the consumer. `` We're expecting it to make shopping more fun, less of a hassle and more efficient for consumers,'' said <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, director for marketing communications at <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which developed the cart. The Chicago-based marketing-research company spent two years inventing the <ORGANIZATION> VideOcart </ORGANIZATION>, with a liquid-crystal-display video screen mounted near the kiddie seat to entertain, inform and offer a few words from the sponsors. Shoppers using <ORGANIZATION> IRI </ORGANIZATION>'s VideOcarts will be able to call up store maps, reserve numbers at the deli counter, find out which checkout line is shortest, play tic tac toe or trivia games to pass the time in line, and get the time, weather forecast or sports scores. The carts would be provided free to the supermarkets, with costs paid by advertisers whose commercials could be transmitted nationally by satellite to local supermarkets. The high-tech carts are to be test-marketed this fall in three stores, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said _ one in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, the others in cities not yet chosen. If the test-marketing goes well, <ORGANIZATION> IRI </ORGANIZATION> plans to introduce the carts in major-city grocery stores in July 1989 and go national in 1991 with carts in 10,000 supermarkets. The video screens will be especially encased to make them `` kid-proof, grape-juice-proof, shock and water resistant,'' with an alarm system to prevent theft, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. Ads will make up about 15 percent of the programming. The rest will be entertainment and information services. <ORGANIZATION> IRI </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malec </PERSON>, who developed the cart introduced in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this week, called it `` the most important new advertising and promotion medium since television.'' Using sensors in the aisles, an ad for coffee or soda pop can be automatically triggered when the cart reaches the area where those products are shelved. The use of in-store advertising _ signs attached to shopping carts, sales pitches on store sound systems and the like _ has burgeoned in recent years, with spending growing 14 percent a year over the past decade to an estimated $ 12.6 billion last year, according to industry estimates. <ORGANIZATION> VideOcart </ORGANIZATION> offers the advantage of packaging the ads with entertainment, said <PERSON> Malec </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> IRI </ORGANIZATION> plans to invest $ 200 million over the next three years in developing the system, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. One food-company official expressed interest in the carts, but said he would want to see the test-market results before making a commitment. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Frahler </PERSON>, retail trade promotion manager for the <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION>, Ill.-based Kitchens of <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a major frozen baked-goods producer, suggested there might be some confusion as shoppers get used to wheeling and viewing. `` There is probably going to be some bumping into each other,'' said <PERSON> Frahler </PERSON>, who viewed the cart in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. But he said `` the concept is fascinating and it seems to be well thought out.''
