<SECOND>PM-Hungry Migrants,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Farmers Charging Migrants High Fees To Fill Out Workers'
Forms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in report for Friday AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORNELIUS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of destitute migrant workers are being victimized by farmers who charge them as much as $ 400 each to prepare false immigration papers, authorities say. As many as 25,000 migrants dependent on social service agencies for food and shelter are in the state, unemployed and waiting for <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s strawberry harvest, the country's second largest after <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s, to begin about June 1. Under the nation's new immigration law, most migrants who picked crops in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for at least 90 days in 1985-86 may qualify as permanent resident aliens and continue to legally enter the country to work in future years. Some farmers are preparing fraudulent documents for migrants who otherwise would not qualify under the law, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Beebe </PERSON>, the district director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. Others demand excessive fees to prepare the documents the migrants must present to federal authorities to fulfill the law's requirements, he said `` The <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is aware of unscrupulous employers ... who are finding new ways to exploit workers,'' <PERSON> Beebe </PERSON> said. He emphasized, however, that the majority of strawberry growers treat pickers fairly. <PERSON> Beebe </PERSON> declined to comment on what steps his agency is taking to deal with the dishonest farmers and their allies, including printers who can prodcuce false rent receipts and other documents. The agricultural workers have until Nov. 30 to file the papers. After that, employers who hire illegal migrant workers will face stiff penalties. The migrants must pay $ 185 each to apply for amnesty under the new law. Fees for physical examinations, pictures and other required documents push the cost to near $ 300. <PERSON> Strawberry </PERSON> farmer <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Krahmer </PERSON> said he has heard of growers charging as much as $ 400 additional to prepare the paperwork. Another grower, who asked not to be identified, said he's heard some farmers are charging $ 250. <PERSON> Krahmer </PERSON> estimated that as many as one-fourth of the migrants are being charged more than $ 25 to help defray the costs involved. He said he charges $ 20 to process paperwork for migrants seeking documentation at his Lloy-Dene Farms near <LOCATION> Cornelius </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Unger </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strawberry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said he knows of no grower charging more than $ 25. `` The ones I know of charge nothing or a nominal fee,'' he said. <PERSON> Krahmer </PERSON> said labor contractors, brokers who sign up and deliver the pickers to growers, are promising the papers to attract workers. Last year, the strawberry crop was harvested early and 20 percent of the crop was left in the fields because not enough workers were in the state. Many pickers say they were told they must turn in their documentation by May 4, the deadline for aliens who are n't involved in agricultural work. Hundreds of migrant pickers, confused by the heavily publicized May deadline, are rushing to <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> offices around the state. The result this year has been an influx of migrants, nearly all men and teen-age boys, weeks before the crop is ready to be picked. Typical of these is 14-year-old <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, who is broke, on his own and a long way from his home. Speaking in Spanish, the teen-ager from <LOCATION> Ensenada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, said he has never picked strawberries in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> before, but that a `` friend'' told him growers would sign the papers he needs to keep returning here to work. The Rev. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zegar </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alexander </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Cornelius </PERSON>, said he believes contractors have drawn migrants to <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> early by falsely promising to arrange their immigration papers. The workers stay in labor camps without money, food and other essentials, he said, waiting for the strawberries to ripen while social service agencies struggle to meet their needs. `` I do n't think anybody has the right to put people into a situation where they have to beg for food and essentials,'' <PERSON> Zegar </PERSON> said. At Centro Cultural, the community center in <LOCATION> Cornelius </LOCATION>, migrants watch Spanish-language television in the lobby and wait for dinner, served Monday through Thursday at 3 p.m. Each day, Centro Cultural serves an average of more than 200 free meals of beans, potatoes and tortillas to the migrants. The <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is meeting the needs of thousands of other migrants, distributing tons of beans, potatoes, rice and flour. The uncertainty over the workforce has led many growers in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> to abandon planting strawberries; plantings for next year are down 75 percent. Plantings are up in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the largest strawberry producer, which has a resident picker population and is n't reliant on foreign labor. Last year, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> produced a bumper crop of 94 million pounds which sold for a record $ 31.5 million.
