<SECOND>PM-Shultz's Woes, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Little Headway In Middle East Or On Soviet Front</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Instead of slowing down, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is stepping on the gas. But the determined secretary of state has little to show for his vigorous diplomatic efforts in these final months of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. He had hoped to open <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks this Sunday, in the first stage of an ambitious <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> program aimed at providing some measure of self-rule to the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs who live on the Israeli-held <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. But despite two trips to the area, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was unable to persuade <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> or King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> to accept his proposal. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says he will keep trying, and will try to find the time to make another personal appeal to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> leaders. But he seems less optimistic than ever before. On the Soviet front, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is making arrangements for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> May 29-June 2 for a fourth and probably final summit meeting with General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The centerpiece was supposed to be a treaty to halve the Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons. But with only a month left, the two sides are still far apart on such issues as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Strategic Defense Initiative and how to monitor the reduction of mobile missiles and other weapons that are relatively easy to conceal. Even the treaty signed at last year's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit to scrap intermediate-range nuclear missiles is still awaiting <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> will try again May 11-12 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. But he appears to be lowering his sights to a summit that would be mostly an exchange of views between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> instead of a historic event. Analysts differ on whether <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s decision to withdraw some 115,000 Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is a victory for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy or a decision taken by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for its own reasons. But on other regional fronts there is little opportunity for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to claim credit. The Soviets are resisting a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plea that they help impose a worldwide arms embargo on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. And they decline to accept a benign role in a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference. `` I did n't achieve any breakthrough,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> admitted Thursday to a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittee about his talks last week in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Taking the long view, he reminded the senators how cool the U.S.-Soviet relationship was in 1985, before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took over. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s human rights pleas now get a respectful hearing, and even some action. Jewish emigration hit a 15-month high last month. Giving the subject `` the pride of place'' on his agenda, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> opened his talks with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> with human rights and kept at it for two hours. In the past, the Soviets mostly listened impassively to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pleas. Now American and Soviet lawyers and psychiatrists are holding meetings to discuss the situation. Otherwise, though, even the climate is worsening. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took sharp exception last week to a speech by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> accusing the Soviets of aggression and other bad behavior. He complained the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` sermonizing'' as well as attributing any improvement in relations to a policy of strength. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> tried to minimize the criticism. He said there was a `` rhythm'' to U.S.-Soviet relations that had both moments of progress and of discord. Other State Department officials were privately critical of the tough rhetoric in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech. They said it had not been submitted to the department for review before delivery. Ever loyal, though, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Thursday that `` we must call it as we see it.''
