<FIRST>r a PM-FishDebts Bjt   04-29 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fish Debts, Bjt,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catch of the Day: Accounts Receivable</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the bustling and often chaotic seafood industry, <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> casts a widening net for what might be the most prized catch of all: Buyers who refuse to pay up. <PERSON> Workman </PERSON>'s work has taken him on predawn visits to ramshackle back offices in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s tough Fulton Fish Market, where prudent debt collectors seldom venture in an industry notorious for its proliferation of deadbeats. Bullhorn in hand, <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> has brazenly entered crowded seafood restaurants at the height of the lunch hour to announce to patrons that the fish on their plates may not have been paid for. `` It's the No. 1 problem in the industry,'' says the former debt collector and sales representative for <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, who has carved out a fast-growing and profitable new business, <ORGANIZATION> Debt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` Fish is in such demand, it's so popular, that it's not hard to sell. It's certainly not hard to sell a <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> lobster. The hard part is to get paid for it.'' Part of the problem is that seafood is a perishable commodity whose value is at its highest when it hits the dock and then diminishes rapidly. `` To get the most for their product before the value drops they have to move it very quickly _ and that means they take unusual risks,'' <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> explained. `` They'll sell to people knowing there's maybe only a 50-50 chance they'll get paid, as opposed to a 100 percent chance that the fish will spoil and become a non-saleable item.'' Because sellers are reluctant to communicate with each other for fear of losing a competitive edge, unscrupulous restaurateurs and wholesalers have been known to switch from supplier to supplier in order to avoid ever having to pay their accounts due, <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> says. To combat such practices, Debt Management semimonthly publishes SeaScan, a continuously updated list of hundreds of seafood markets, restaurants, wholesalers, brokers and distributors who are in arrears on their debts. The publication, about 50 pages long, consists of yellow pages with the names of buyers whose payments are at least 30 days past due; red pages listing buyers whose accounts have been referred to the company for collection; and white pages, tagged the `` rubber sheet,'' which lists buyers whose checks have bounced. `` Yellow is slow, red has stopped,'' <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> explains. `` Everyone who has stopped paying his bills slowed down first.'' SeaScan is distributed to his company's more than 200 clients, ranging from salmon harvesters in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shetland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> to catfish producers in the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> to shrimp importers on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. A seller who purchases the SeaScan report and becomes a Debt Management client can refer past due accounts to <PERSON> Workman </PERSON>'s company, which receives a percentage of the overdue receivables it collects in addition to a $ 2,500 a year membership fee. The 33-year-old <LOCATION> Nyack </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, native, who began the business three years ago in his home, today has 17 employees and subsidiary offices in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. He says his clients are among the largest in the industry, accounting for nearly half the dollar volume of seafood sold in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> has n't emerged unscathed from deadbeat raids. He recalls the time three fish cutters grabbed him by the jacket at a seafood wholesaler's in <LOCATION> Pompano </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and tossed him unceremoniously onto the sidewalk. But while inside the establishment, <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> had spotted some boxes bearing the name of one of his major clients. He immediately telephoned the client and apprised him of the situation; the client, in turn, called the wholesaler and threatened to cut off future shipments if he did n't pay the debt. Waiting for <PERSON> Workman </PERSON> when he returned was an apology and a check for $ 15,000.
