<HEAD>Death Toll Rising As Wind and Tides Threaten To Spread Slick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strong wind and rising tides hampered the cleanup of a 175,000-gallon oil spill and posed a new threat to a fragile bird sanctuary where nearly 200 oil-soaked birds and animals have died. `` The good news is the oil is no longer getting out of <PERSON> Peyton </PERSON> <PERSON> Slough </PERSON>, where 80 percent of it was trapped, but the bad news is that what's out there in the strait and bays is going to get swirled around a bit by nature,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Zawadzki </PERSON> said Thursday. Meanwhile, a state water quality engineer speculated the size of <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s spill may be even larger than the 175,000 gallons estimated by the company. The spill occurred Saturday when a drainpipe that carries off rainwater broke inside an oil tank, allowing oil to be siphoned out. So far workers have recovered some 126,000 gallons of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> crude, a particularly thick oil, from the area 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said. Because much of the oil remains in <PERSON> Peyton </PERSON> <PERSON> Slough </PERSON> and nearby marshes, <PERSON> Kazemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hossain </PERSON>, an engineer with the state <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> board, told reporters he expects <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> `` will revise upwards their spill estimate, after we do our own calculations.'' Earlier Thursday, westerly winds up to 25 mph and increasingly higher tides pushed up to 1,600 gallons of oil out of remote sloughs into the <LOCATION> Carquinez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> and into still more waterfowl nesting areas. Similar gusts were expected today, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecasters said. By the weekend, easterly winds and exceptionally high weekend tides _ peaking about 5 feet _ are likely to send still more oil into uncontaminated areas, <PERSON> Zawadzki </PERSON> said. Eight skimmer boats on Thursday began removing new oil-sheen patches stretching six miles from <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Marina </PERSON>, where 400 boats were trapped in the oily harbor, to <LOCATION> Ryer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where the the oil got into nesting areas. Some 450 oily waterfowl and animals have been recovered. Of those, 192 have died or were dead when discovered, according to <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, regional manager of the state Fish and Game Department. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> advised sport fishing and recreational boats owners to stay out of <LOCATION> Suisun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> over the weekend, where several oil sheens were spotted. The bay is about 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Boat skippers, many of whom make a living by taking out weekend parties of sports fishermen, were upset they would not be allowed out to sea Sunday for the opening of the salmon season. They also could not leave the marina for the <LOCATION> Sacramento-San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delta </LOCATION>, where steelhead trout are approaching the peak of their spawning season. `` This is going to be a big blow to a lot of old timers around here because they count on getting out to sea and getting a good catch early in the season when they can get the best price,'' said <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Torliano </PERSON>, 74, whose son operates a family fishing