<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     04-29 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Railroad Car Shortage Hampers Grain Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Robust export demand and failure to add to the fleet since 1982 have caused a shortage of railroad cars to move wheat and corn, says a transportation official with the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Although the car shortages appear to have eased in recent days, steps need to be taken to avoid a repetition of the crunch that occurred earlier this year, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, head of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> also defended <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> export policies and programs which have helped trigger a rebound in farm commodity exports. A study released by <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> showed a severe disruption of grain shipments in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year through mid-April because of shortages of covered hopper cars used by railroads. The study was requested by Reps. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Slattery </PERSON>, D-Kan., and <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, R-Neb <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said he planned to cite the study further at a hearing on Monday, May 2, in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, conducted by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said the actual number of cars available for grain movement has been both shrinking and aging since 1982 when the last significant number was added to the railroad fleet. Also, there has been a large surge in export wheat sales under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, during the past few months. Big sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, in particular, have added to the railroad grain traffic. Under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, exporters can sell wheat or other designated commodities to an approved foreign country at reduced prices and then collect subsidies from <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> in the form of government-owned surplus grain or other agricultural products. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said car shortages meant some local elevators were unable to take delivery of grain from farmers, grain merchants had difficulty completing sales, and railroads hiked rates and restricted use of cars in certain markets. Also, he said, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` received limited response'' to its weekly auctions of surplus wheat because of the car shortages. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> was asked by a reporter whether the rail car shortages had interfered with shipments of grain to seaports to the extent that ships were kept waiting for grain to load. `` We do not believe that to be the case, as a general rule,'' he said. But there may have been `` some specific circumstances'' what that happened in the last six months. `` It's not a trend, it is not a significant problem down the road,'' <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said. Although reasons are not clear why the hopper car situation has improved the last 10 days, <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> noted that export demand has slackened somewhat and delivery dates have eased. Also, he said, railroads had received overbookings for cars from grain companies, and many of those now are being reconciled. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said that it will take pressure from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, farm groups, the grain trade and <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to settle the rail car situation. Ideally, he said, shippers and the railroads should sit down under auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and resolve the problems. The <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION>, he said, has the authority to force a settlement. <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> was asked if he thought the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> was dragging its feet. `` All I would say to you is the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> has full authority to resolve this issue,'' he said. `` It's been almost six years that they have had it on their table, so you draw your own conclusion.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm policy could be improved worldwide by making government support to farmers independent of acreage and production levels, says the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> and Agricultural Policy. This policy of decoupling would lead to `` more efficient production of agricultural goods and lower production costs when compared to current farm policies,'' the center reported Thursday. Some form of decoupling for American farmers has been advocated unsuccessfully in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for a number of years. One example would be to sign up farmers in a crop program and provide benefits without tying them to specific acreage or production levels. As defined by the center _ a part of the independent, non-profit Washington-based think tank, Resources for the Future _ decoupling would mean `` providing government support to farmers in ways that do not distort production, prices, consumption, resource allocation or trade.'' Decoupling does n't set well with some farm groups. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, for example, says it is tantamount to putting farmers on welfare by substituting direct federal payments for price supports. A statement issued by <ORGANIZATION> NFU </ORGANIZATION> at its recent annual convention said: `` Farmers want federal program payments to help recover their cost of producing food. These payments are actually subsidies to consumers that pass through the hands of farmers.''
</TEXT>
