<HEAD>Agreement Doesn't Keep Congress From Arguing Over Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last fall's deficit-reduction agreement was supposed to make this an easy year for passing a budget, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have managed to get in an argument anyway. Talks between the chambers on a compromise $ 1.1 trillion spending plan collapsed Thursday amid angry accusations of bad-faith negotiating. `` That which I fear the worst has befallen me,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., who is retiring after this year, citing `` burnout'' from his three terms <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> blasted <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> negotiators for sending an offer on the fiscal 1989 spending plan not `` in the spirit of what we sent you.'' He told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in colorful words usually impolite in public meetings, it should not expect a response and should come back with a new proposal. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa., the House budget chairman, took offense `` I'm not going to sit here and be told, ` If you do n't like what we offered, then lump it,''' he said. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> offered to negotiate through the weekend, but <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said he was heading back to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for next week, when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is on recess. `` When the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> makes an offer that moves as far to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> did to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, send it to me by wire and I'll come back,'' he told <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>. Another meeting was set for May 9 but <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> warned: `` We'd better get on our seersucker suits and turn on the air conditioning I think we're going into summer.'' Last fall's deficit-reduction pact between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and congressional leaders laid down the outlines for the budget for the spending year beginning next Oct. 1. It settled what is usually the biggest fight _ `` guns versus butter'' _ by providing specific figures for overall military, foreign aid and domestic spending. The budgets approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, however, took slightly different approaches toward the domestic budget. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, led by <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, approved a bigger increase in the space program, which is well-represented in his home state. The House has refused to go along, favoring more spending on housing and poverty programs. Another issue is a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan to alter the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agreement to add more drug-fighting money. House members oppose breaking the summit pact for drugs alone, and not aid for the homeless and other needs. Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, senior Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel, said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> `` nitpicking'' was threatening to `` make an absolute joke out of this process.'' `` We were supposed to have a year where the -LRB- budget -RRB- summit made it easy,'' he said. Now, he said, `` we're about to destroy it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> must compromise on the budget before it becomes the official guide for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' annual spending bills. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> missed its April 15 deadline for completing the budget resolution. If one is n't approved by the middle of next month the two chambers will begin passing their spending bills without one. Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., a budget committee member, urged that heads remain cool and emphasized that differences were not great `` All we've got to do is agree to have an easy time'' he said.
