<HEAD>States Get Low Grades in Handling of Complaints Against Lawyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who complain about their lawyers are out of luck in most states if they expect help from the agency that is supposed to regulate the profession, a legal reform group says. A `` report card'' issued Thursday by HALT, a consumer advocacy organization campaigning to reform the attorney discipline process, gave most states surveyed an `` F'' in policing lawyers. `` Nobody is doing a good job _ the question is how bad,'' <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostberg </PERSON>, HALT's director of research and education, said at news conference. But the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which says it also is working for reforms, insists there have been improvements in recent years. `` I would say that most of the states are doing a reasonably good job given the resources they have,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> McPike </PERSON>, who handles matters involving professional standards. HALT says disciplinary agencies often have a conflict of interest because they are run by lawyers and because the disciplinary process itself is mired in secrecy. In many states, the public never learns which lawyers are being investigated or the outcome of the probe. The most common complaints are of excessive legal fees or an attorney's neglect. Ms. <PERSON> Ostberg </PERSON> said disciplinary agencies do n't usually act unless the offense is shown to be excessive She cited a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> survey of 40 states which found that 54,605 complaints were received but only 1,146 or 2 percent resulted in any form of public discipline. Ninety-five percent were dismissed without any discipline. <PERSON> McPike </PERSON> says those numbers reflect that many complaints are not serious enough to warrant action. `` Ninety percent of the complaints do n't even make it past the first screening. People complain because their lawyer did n't answer their phone call fast enough,'' he said. `` You have to have a good, strong case before you can take somebody's license from them.'' HALT proposed speeding up the process of dealing with complaints, opening records to the public and having non-lawyers serve on independent commissions to monitor and investigate complaints. <PERSON> McPike </PERSON> said that in 1985, the most recent year for which figures are available, 20 states made disciplinary proceedings public after it was determined there was probable cause to warrant the filing of charges. Thirty-three states have non-lawyers serving on disciplinary boards, he said. Complaints are handled on the state level by organizations operated under the state's highest court. These organizations are run as arms of state bar associations or as separate disciplinary governing boards. The HALT survey, conducted during February and March, graded disciplinary agencies in five categories: whether the agency is subject to public review or control, allows public access to its proceedings, makes disciplinary records public, encourages the filing of complaints and has a `` fair and responsive'' disciplinary process. Thirty-three states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> responded to the survey. The rest of the states did not respond. HALT gave each state that responded a `` final grade'' based on the five criteria: <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, D; <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, D +; <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, D; <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, D; <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, F; <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>