<TEXT>
 The blast that ripped a huge hole in an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> appears to be unlike any previous accident involving <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planes, say officials of the aircraft company. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, the main <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, said Thursday night they had received only sketchy reports of the explosion, which ripped off the top of the fuselage just behind the cockpit to about the wing, injuring 60 people and leaving one person missing. Both executives said there were no fuel lines or other potential sources for an explosion in the first-class cabin, just behind the cockpit, where passengers on the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-200 reported that the blast occurred. `` The fuel is in the wing, the engines are in the wing and the fuel lines are all right there,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home. Even in the extremely unlikely event that a turbine blade tore loose from one of the two engines and ripped into the fuselage in mid-flight, it could not hit forward from the wing and the effect would be nothing like what happened to the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> plane, he said. `` To have it just explode in the air is just unheard of,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` I think this is a very unusual circumstance that is not related to any other accidents we have had.'' <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents were sent from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> to check the possibility that a bomb might have been put on the plane, said <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSO