<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s angry charge that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was impeding the trial of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and three Iran-Contra co-defendants was a performance familar to lawyers who frequent his courtroom. A day after <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> accused the administration of intentionally withholding classified documents that he says the defendants were entitled to see, the veteran federal judge calmly acknowledged the government's fears about disclosing some of its most sensitive secrets. Having angrily said Wednesday that `` a stone wall is being built up between this court and the trial,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> took the bench in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday and discussed the problem in milder tones. He blandly described it as an `` obstacle caused by concerns in the government generally concerning the confidentiality of documents'' and offered `` to see if I can be of any help to this situation.'' The switch in the judge's courtroom demeanor was described by one lawyer as `` typical <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> _ bark, bark bark, meow, meow, meow.'' Another lawyer, who also did not want to be personally associated with a comment about a sitting judge, said <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> `` blows hot and cold.'' Despite his changed demeanor, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> did not retreat Thursday from his earlier threat to dismiss the case unless the relevant classified documents are shown to the defense and made available for use at trial as evidence. That possibility is a very real one, particularly if independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> is unable to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> or other national security agencies to declassify sensitive documents <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> decides are needed as evidence for the defense. `` The government is obliged to make all relevant information available in some reasonable way to the defense and using the monolithic term ` government' might not be appropriate where the independent counsel really does not call the shots,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Veniste </PERSON>, a former Watergate prosecutor. Lawyers for <PERSON> North </PERSON>, former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and businessmen <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, will be looking closely for material they can predict wo n't be declassified. As former guardians of some of the nation's most sensitive secrets, <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> are in a unique position to help their lawyers find evidence that is beyond the court's reach. A successful search of the 300,000 pages of sensitive material collected by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> could lead to dismissal of charges they conspired to illegally divert profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels. At an earlier hearing, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> referred to the complicated procedures for handling sensitive documents and remarked that <PERSON> North </PERSON> `` knows more about the methods than those in the classification system.'' With secret documents deemed relevant and admissable as evidence `` you end up with the double D's: declassify or dismiss,'' said defense lawyer <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who once prosecuted anti-terrorism cases for the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't know of any case since the Classified Information Procedures Act was passed not quite 10 years ago that has ever had the volume of relevant classified material that this one does,'' he said. The law contains elaborate procedures for determining whether classified material is relevant evidence for the prosecution and the defense. If the government wo n't declassify a document, it allows for deletions of secret material of substitution of summaries to enable the introduction of relevant evidence. But not all documents can be easily altered or summarized and <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he wo n't spend much time on that process, particularly since <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> says 50,000 pages are relevant to the case. `` What is the government going to do, or the judge going to do if the government says ` we ca n't declassify this, It is just too sensitive'?'' <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON> said. The problem is particularly acute in the Iran-Contra case because `` the essence of some of the crimes that are charged is classified activity,'' he said. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> diGenova </PERSON>, who recently resigned as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney here, noted that `` it may very well be that some of that stuff is so sensitive under no circumstances should it be released.'' And if <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> is forced to dismiss the charges because there is too much classified evidence, `` so be it,'' <PERSON> diGenova </PERSON> said. `` That was how the statute was designed. That is the way it is supposed to work.''
</TEXT>
