<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0866 04-29 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0866,0964</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Chess,' A New Musical By Tim Rice and ABBA, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with other reviews; no PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Life is just a game played out on a big checkered board, or so they seem to be saying in `` Chess,'' the heavy-handed British musical hit that lumbered into Broadway's Imperial Theater on Thursday night In this case, it's the theatergoers who are checkmated, trapped for more than three hours in a cold and unappealing musical that ranks as one of the season's biggest disappointments. That's surprising considering the show boasts a provocative, tuneful score with lyrics by <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> and music by <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bjorn </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulvaeus </PERSON>, two members of the pop group <ORGANIZATION> ABBA </ORGANIZATION>. But the songwriters are shortchanged by director <PERSON> Trevor </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and playwright <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> who have fashioned a musical that is big on metaphor and short on credibility, not to mention entertainment. The plot, apparently reworked a bit from the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> production, is a romantic triangle involving a volatile and vulgar <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> chess champion -LRB- <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Casnoff </PERSON> -RRB-, his Soviet opponent -LRB- <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> -RRB- and the American's second -LRB- <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> -RRB-, a Hungarian refugee who falls for the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> at the drop of a rook. The American is sort of the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McEnroe </PERSON> of chess. The champion's manners _ and politics _ are somewhere to the right of <PERSON> Genghis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>. His distastefulness dulls one point of this love triangle, making it hard for the audience to wonder who will end up with whom, let alone who will win the big match. The triangle eventually becomes a quartet when it is revealed that the Russian has a wife -LRB- <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitzman </PERSON> -RRB- back in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. She does n't show up until the second act, and by then the story has bogged down completely. The three chess players are manipulated by an assortment of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents as well as public relations types who sing and dance their way through the show. Everyone is the pawn of someone else, a soap opera message <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> reiterates with numbing frequency. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, who previously worked wonders on `` Cats,'' `` Les Miserables'' and `` The Life and Adventures of <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickleby </PERSON>,'' falters with this show. Like `` <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Miserables </PERSON>,'' `` Chess'' relies on a turntable to make the musical move. But it does n't work as well. Set designer <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> provides a series of gray, concrete-like columns that glide, swivel and turn around the stage. Their perpetual motion eventually becomes monotonous and even irritating. Much of the time, the characters just stand on stage and shout _ at each other or toward the audience. There's not much <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> can do with these argumentative moments, but when a number cries out for some musical movement, it does n't get any help. Consider the exotic song `` One Night in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>,'' a sizable pop success several years ago, and virtually thrown away here in an embarrassing flesh-peddling scene that looks like it was borrowed from a summer stock revival of `` The World of <PERSON> Suzie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>.'' The show has been cast with strong voices, even down to the smallest roles. At a result, many of the songs soar in spite of the story. Miss <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> has a radiant voice, and when she does n't push it, the sound embraces the theater. Her quiet moments are the best, particularly `` Heaven Help My Heart,'' a delicate solo, and `` I Know Him So Well,'' a duet of commiseration that Miss <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> sings with the Russian's neglected wife. The songwriters also have provided some memorable music for the men, particularly the bitter `` Pity the Child,'' which contains <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>'s finest lyrics. It's an explanation by the American grand master as to why he turned out to be such a rotter. <PERSON> Casnoff </PERSON> succeeds too well in conveying the character's miserable personality. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, who possesses an even better voice, manages to make the Russian more than a milquetoast, not an inconsiderable achievement, considering <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s laborious plot. The performer brings the overlong first act to a thrilling conclusion with a ringing anthem to his homeland. As good as the score is, there is too much of it. The songwriters added several songs for the American production, including `` Someone Else's Story,'' one number that has likely pop potential. But less would have been more. The costumes by <PERSON> Theoni </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldredge </PERSON> are undistinguished, all-purpose modern clothes that are remarkably ordinary and, in the case of Miss <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON>, unflattering. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersey </PERSON>'s lighting at least tries to bathe <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s dozen or so behemoth columns in a soft, humanizing glow. It's that humane, personal quality which is missing from the rest of the production. The musical revels in its political message and its conceit of a chess game as a microcosm of real life. Not even the fine handiwork of its three gifted songwriters can make the sledgehammer symbolism of `` Chess'' palatable. In other reviews: <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> writes in the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> that Chess is `` a show without a game plan. ... `` The characters are cliches, and not even appropriate ones. ... Neither of the love stories is emotionally involving. ... Visually ` Chess' is drab. ... The show is shrilly overamplified. ... `` The lingering question ... is why anyone imagined international politics was something to sing about.'' In The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> writes: `` Rather than condescend to throwing the audience a bone of genuinely romantic or melodramatic entertainment _ or even providing a tense chess game _ the authors pass the time pontificating about politics in sweeping generalities reminiscent of Mr. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>'s ` Evita.''' Referring to `` the musical's metaphorical equation of chess and war,'' <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> says: `` War is hell, and ... ` Chess' sometimes comes remarkably close.''
</TEXT>
