<HEAD>Danish Cheese Recalled Because of Bacterium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Food and Drug Administration says the importer of e <ORGANIZATION> Castello </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Danish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cheese </ORGANIZATION> has been recalled its product because some samples showed a bacterium that can cause flu-like symptoms. The agency said Thursday more than 2,000, 35-ounce pieces of the cheese sent to distributors in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> are being recalled. They recalled cheeses were in cartons coded TCU213 and the individual pieces have the lot number 02X on their wrappers. The cheese was made by <PERSON> Tholstrup </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheese </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, and imported by <ORGANIZATION> Tholstrup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cheese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warren </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said the bacterium, Listeria monocytogenes, occasionally can be life-threatening to pregnant women and their fetuses, frail elderly people and others with weakened immune systems.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Measure Expanding Services To Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has signed a multibillion-dollar education measure expanding services to students. In a signing ceremony on Thursday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the measure `` reauthorizes and improves a wide variety of federal programs at the elementary and secondary school level.'' More than half of the $ 8.3 billion authorized in the bill will go to disadvantaged children at risk of failing. It contains new programs to prevent dropouts and help high school students with weak skills, and greatly expands drug abuse education and magnet schools. New money also was earmarked for math, science and foreign-language programs. The largest single program in the measure will pay for tutoring and other services to disadvantaged children who are in danger of failing academically. Other initiatives in the bill include $ 50 million for `` Even Start,'' to jointly educate poor preschool children and their illiterate parents; $ 50 million for dropout prevention demonstration projects; and $ 200 million to improve basic skills of high school students.
