n't need the painting. It's worth a lot more to me, from an artistic standpoint and for my family.'' The painting was valued at $ 2,000 when it was auctioned, <PERSON> Likan </PERSON> said, adding that he believes it would be worth $ 8,000 today. `` It could be anyplace,'' said Capt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zurawski </PERSON> of the police department's financial investigation unit. `` It's like looking for a needle in a haystack. `` I used to work at the galleries,'' <PERSON> Zurawski </PERSON> said. `` Paintings go for cash usually, and the buyer is usually just an initial.''
