<HEAD>Emperor Celebrates 87th Birthday, Reflects On Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people shouted `` Banzai'' and waved Japanese flags as Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, the world's oldest and longest-reigning monarch, appeared briefly on his palace balcony today to mark his 87th birthday. The emperor's birthday is a national holiday. `` Thank you for celebrating my birthday with me today. I am happy that so many of you have come today. I hope you will all have a happy future,'' <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> said from behind bullet-proof glass in a speech carried live on national television. It was his second public appearance since he underwent surgery last September to bypass a tumor blocking his digestive tract. Doctors later said the growth was not malignant. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, once worshiped as a living god, also spoke to well-wishers at the Imperial Palace grounds on New Year's Day. <PERSON> Nobuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimane </PERSON>, an accountant in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, was one of the estimated 35,000 who came in three shifts under a drizzling rain today and stood in a palace courtyard to see the emperor in his annual birthday appearance. `` I think this will be the last chance to see him because of his advanced age,'' <PERSON> Shimane </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has been on the throne since Dec. 25, 1926. Despite rumors of ill health, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> appeared relatively strong today, although he shuffled slowly as he walked. He was accompanied by Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> and Princess <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON> and other members of the imperial family. Missing was Empress <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON>, 85, who suffers back and leg ailments. In a news conference marking his birthday, the emperor said he was recovering well from surgery and answered questions about his memories of World War II. `` After all is considered, the war was my most unpleasant memory. I am pleased with people's efforts for peace after the war. Hereafter, I hope the people do not forget this matter and protect peace,'' <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> said. He refused to say what caused <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to enter the war in the first place, saying, `` I do not want to answer the question because this will involve criticism against persons.'' Foreign reporters were not alowed to attend the news conference, which was conducted Monday but not released until today. The remarks were carried in Japanese by the <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and translated by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. During two previous news conferences for foreign reporters _ the last 13 years ago _ the emperor expressed his personal sorrow for `` certain things'' that happened during World War II. But he said he acted as a constitutional monarch before and during the war and did not play a personal role. He also denied planning the <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> attack, but left many other questions unanswered. During this year's news conference, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Yoshihiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Tokugawa </PERSON>, his former grand chamberlain who retired earlier this month at the age of 81 after serving for more than half a century. `` He protected recordings of the emperor's announcement of defeat in the war -LRB- from soldiers who intruded into the Imperial Palace on Aug. 15, 1945 -RRB-. With his language abilities, he prepared well for my friendly visits to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> so that my visits were successful.'' Soldiers had planned to seize the recording so the war could continue. They beat <PERSON> Tokugawa </PERSON> with a pistol, but he refused to say where the recording was hidden. When the disk was finally played, it was the first time most Japanese heard their emperor's voice. During that broadcast, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> urged his subjects `` to open an era of grand peace for the generations to come, by suffering the insufferable, bearing the unbearable.'' However, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> never used the words `` surrender'' or `` defeat.'' <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> also said in the interview that it would take him a long time to complete his research in marine biology, his favorite hobby. He said he had replanted an endangered plant species and `` it is growing well because the imperial garden is similar to forest land.''
