on must be reduced but said he would not take part in a `` witchhunt of immigrants.'' For <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, 55, the key to winning the May 8 runoff election could lie with capturing the votes of those who favor <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, leader of the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, running on an anti-immigration platform, achieved a stunning success in Sunday's first round of the presidential elections, garnering 14.4 percent of the vote, compared to 19.9 percent for <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, 71, won with 34 percent. On Sunday, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> is to advise his sympathizers how to vote on May 8. He has publicly ruled out votes in <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s favor. But he has said he is looking for concrete signs <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and his neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic would implement policies in keeping with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s goals. Thursday night's two-hour forum, in which two well-known journalists asked the questions, was billed as the major political event. The number of immigrants `` must of course be reduced,'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said during the exchange. But he added that immigration was `` an exaggerated problem, sometimes purposely complicated ... that can not be treated without nuance.'' `` I will not participate during this presidential election in a witchhunt of immigrants,'' he said. `` Very simply, immigration must be stopped because <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> no longer has the means to give work to foreigners,'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> said. `` It is an imperious necessity.'' Using a term dear to <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, he added, `` It's a problem of national identity, of the French way of life.'' `` You did n't wink there, did you?'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> interjected. The president appeared to command the first half of the debate, but <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> responded confidently and with animation on the subjects of immigration, taxes and security.
