<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> today denounced a television documentary that contradicted the official version of the killing of three unarmed <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas by British commandos. `` The freedom of people depends on the rule of law, a fair legal system,'' she told a Japanese television interviewer. `` The place to have trials is a court of law. Trial by TV or guilt by accusation is the day that freedom dies.'' Television authorities rejected a government request to delay the broadcast, and the hourlong documentary `` Death on the Rock'' aired Thursday night. The program said the guerrillas died while trying to flee or surrender to the commandos in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>. Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> had said the guerrillas `` made movements which led security personnel to believe their lives were in danger.'' <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said it received scores of calls after the broadcast, running about 3-2 against the decision to screen the film. <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> called the broadcast `` grossly and wholly improper'' and said in a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio interview that it had `` inevitably'' been shown on satellite TV in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>, where it might influence an inquest jury. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, legal political arm of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, said the allegations showed clearly the guerrillas were `` summarily executed.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> program featured people due to testify at the inquest in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> and complained that their accounts would influence the hearing. It had asked <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, chairman of the controlling <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, to delay broadcasting the program. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> turned down the request, denied the documentary would prejudice the inquest and said postponement would give the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> more `` oxygen of publicity.'' <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> said the documentary was the result of a seven-week investigation which included interviews with 150 residents of apartments overlooking the area where the guerrillas were shot March 6. In the documentary, translator <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Proetta </PERSON> said she saw the shootings from her apartment window in the British colony that borders <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Proetta </PERSON> said she saw three armed men in plainclothes get out of a police car, jump over a metal barrier in the road and open fire on two of the guerrillas, later identified as <PERSON> Mairead </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, 31, and <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> McCann </PERSON>, 30. `` When they -LRB- Ms. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> and <PERSON> McCann </PERSON> -RRB- saw these men had guns in their hands, they just put their hands up ... There was no chance. I mean they went to the floor immediately, they dropped,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Proetta </PERSON> said. She described the guerrillas' action in putting their hands up as `` like giving themselves up.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Proetta </PERSON> said that after the initial shooting, which she said occurred without warning, `` a blond gunman bent down and with the two hands he got his gun like that