<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> talks aimed at shoring up oil prices bogged down early today in a technical debate that one cartel leader called a `` waste of time.'' A nearly four-hour meeting over a proposal to cut oil exports in conjunction with independent producers broke up early today without any agreements, and leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> said they would reconvene this evening. They said no agreements had been reached. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, the oil minister of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, told reporters later that it was impossible to predict whether an accord could be reached, since `` there's a wide divergence'' of views among the 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members. The oil ministers are considering a proposal from six non-OPEC oil producers to cut both groups' exports by 5 percent in an effort to push <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil prices back to $ 18 a barrel. The non-OPEC group says it will cut its exports only if <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> does likewise. But opinions differ sharply within the cartel over whether further cutbacks are needed, and there are indications some members _ including influential <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> _ favor enforcement of existing output quotas over new cuts. World oil prices continued sliding early today as the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> leaders struggled to resolve their differences. On the European market, <ORGANIZATION> Brent </ORGANIZATION> crude oil from the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> was down 35 cents a barrel, at $ 16.80, at mid-afternoon after having lost 30 cents on Thursday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil markets had n't yet opened. Traders said the declines reflected doubts that the oil ministers' meeting would produce a concrete agreement on measures designed to boost the oil market. Prices have fallen this year because supplies have risen faster than demand. Most OPEC crudes are selling for $ 16 a barrel or less, although oil traded in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> usually sells for more. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, June contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the most widely traded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, fell 29 cents to $ 17.98 dollars a barrel on Thursday after dropping 33 cents the day before. Prices on European markets fell about 30 cents a barrel on Thursday. Some industry analysts believe prices would rebound if <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> accepted the non-OPEC offer. But others doubt that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> could agree on reductions large enough to make a difference in the global balance of supply and demand. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s opening debate focused more on differing views of the oil market's supply and demand balance than on the merits of the non-OPEC group's proposal, according to sources who spoke on condition they not be identified by name or nationality. In an apparent effort to bridge the gap in these views, the oil ministers instructed a team of experts from each member country to meet today to assess the present and near-term market balance. <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Grisanti </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s oil minister, told reporters he was unhappy that time was being devoted to a meeting of experts, which he said only would highlight the differing views between <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries. `` This is, in some sense, a waste of time,'' he said. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said one suggestion under consideration was to forego the proposed export cuts in favor of recommitting the 13 members to existing oil production quotas, which often are violated. `` We know that several countries have been overproducing for years,'' he said, without naming the countries. `` ... If we can have a full guarantee that these countries are going to abide by their quotas, that would improve the market situation. But I have a lot of doubt about that,'' he said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was alone among the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members in stating its clear support for the non-OPEC offer. None have rejected it outright. <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> oil minister, declined to say whether his country favored the non-OPEC proposal, made Wednesday by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. But Saudi King Fahd on Thursday bolstered the impression of many industry analysts that he would not accept any cuts in <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production or exports. He said the cartel's main goal should be to stick to its existing production limits. `` I believe prices will go up if we adhere to the output ceiling and convince non-OPEC producers of the feasibility of limiting their production,'' he said in an interview published by a Kuwaiti newspaper. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacoboski </PERSON>, who was observing the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON>'s statement was `` the real nail in the coffin'' of expectations that the cartel would accept the non-OPEC proposal.
