<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Prem </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinsulanonda </PERSON> dissolved his Cabinet and the Parliament today and called new elections in a dispute over legislation to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> copyrights. The official Radio <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> said general elections would be held July 24. Earlier today, 16 Cabinet ministers belonging to the main party in <LOCATION> Prem </LOCATION>'s coalition government submitted their resignations after failing to stop party dissidents from voting against the government-backed bill to protect American copyrights. The <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ministers _ representing about a third of the Cabinet _ resigned because `` they could not control'' the party dissidents, said Col. <PERSON> Sanan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kachornprasat </PERSON>, the party's secretary general. The radio announcement said <PERSON> Prem </PERSON> and would continue at his post until the election. Prem, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s longest-serving prime minster, has headed five Cabinets since assuming his post in 1980. The last general election was held in 1986. The dissolution of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> forestalled a probable opposition motion to censure the government over its handling of various issues, including economic problems and recent border clashes with <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. The censure motion had been expected May 9. The House of Representatives passed the copyright bill 183-134 on Thursday, but 32 legislators in the dissident group joined members of opposition parties in voting against it. The dissidents said the legislation, which protects <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> copyrights of artistic and literary works, would force <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to bow to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bullying. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had indicated that it might be forced to cut duty privileges for Thai imports if