Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that killed eight people and injured 56. <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON>'s former second-in-command, <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Melkonian </PERSON>, formed a splinter group called ASALA-Revolutionary Movement after the <LOCATION> Orly </LOCATION> bombing, complaining that <ORGANIZATION> ASALA </ORGANIZATION> had abandoned its original policy of focusing only on Turkish targets. <ORGANIZATION> ASALA </ORGANIZATION> has claimed only one attack in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, the killing of Turkish diplomat <PERSON> Galip </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozman </PERSON> and his daughter in August 1980. The group's political wing, the <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, has operated an office in the Greek capital for several years. Turkish officials say 300,000 Armenians died after Ottoman Empire officials deported the country's 1.4 million Armenians to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> during World War I. Independent historians say at least 600,000 Armenians died during the journey.
