t was clearly concerned the labor unrest might spread. Sunday is May Day, international Labor Day and a traditional time of anti-government protest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Miodowicz </PERSON>, a member of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION>, was dispatched Thursday to the Lenin mill. He is national head of the officially sanctioned trade unions. Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Zdzislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadowski </PERSON>, who the official new agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said would appear on television to discuss the economy, postponed a visit today to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to meet with <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> officials. <PERSON> Sadowski </PERSON> is chief architect of the government's effort to make the economy more market-oriented through reforms that have included the price increases. The unofficial strike committee at <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, whose 16 members include Solidarity activists, have demanded a 50 percent increase of the average monthly pay of $ 105. It also said the $ 15 paid monthly in compensation nationwide for recent price increases should be doubled for industrial workers, teachers, health care workers and retirees. This week's labor unrest is the most serious in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since strikes in 1980 over food price increases that spawned Solidarity and brought down a government. The unrest ended with the December 1981 imposition of martial law. On Monday, transit workers in the northwestern city of <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> staged an 11-hour strike and won a 60 percent raise. A day later, the strike began at the <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> works.
