<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--InfantDeaths     04-29 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Infant Deaths,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Reports Infant Mortality Decreasing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of infant deaths in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has decreased, according to a report by the federal health officials. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that for every 1,000 live births in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1984-85, premature deaths robbed those infants under age 1 of 694 years of life they would have had if they had lived to be age 65. That was down 7 percent from the average of 749 years for 1980-83. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> measures `` years of potential life lost'' _ by people dying before 65 _ as a way to gauge the killers of younger people. Sixty-five is used as a statistical benchmark; most Americans' life expectancy is higher. Since the number of infant deaths depends in part on the number of infant births, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> looked at the `` years of potential life lost'' averages to gauge trends in infant mortality. Deaths of infants between birth and age 1 take the greatest amount of `` potential life'' of all; in 1985, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recorded 40,000 such deaths. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> found that between 1980-83 and the period 1984-85, the `` years of potential life lost'' due to prematurity and low birthweight, respiratory distress, birth trauma and other factors went down for both black and white infants. The Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, in its weekly report, particularly noted a sharp drop in potential life lost to birth trauma and asphyxia _ down 33 percent for whites and 31 percent for blacks. `` It makes us curious to look at why,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said that `` the marked decline ... due to birth trauma -LRB- or -RRB- asphyxia'' suggests either better care for newborns at birth, better neonatal care for babies suffering from birth trauma or asphyxia, or both. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> also found that non-white infants die prematurely more often than whites, although death rates for both groups are declining. `` Although there were fewer years of potential life lost for -LRB- both -RRB- whites and blacks, there's still a big gap between those two groups,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Dianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. In recent years, she noted, `` there have been programs and strategies initiated to try and diminish the excess numbers of deaths among blacks and other minorities. It will be a while before we can evaluate those efforts.''
</TEXT>
