<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Scientists Study Simulated Nukes in the Nevada Desert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GERLACH, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A team of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Soviet scientists headed into the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> desert today to begin a series of experiments they hope will prove that a cheat-proof ban on all testing is possible. The experiments today and Saturday come on the heels of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s passage of a bill Thursday forbidding all but the smallest nuclear tests, if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to do the same. Scores of seismic monitors have been set up to record three non-nuclear explosions in remote areas of the state to try to demonstrate that if a U.S.-Soviet test ban treaty is signed, any infraction could be detected. If the experiments are successful, they would show that `` any chance for cheating are about excluded'' under a test ban, <PERSON> Evgeni </PERSON> <PERSON> Velikhov </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. <PERSON> Velikhov </PERSON>, an adviser to <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said, `` We think the comprehensive test ban is very important. It is extremely important to stop the arms race.'' The experiment is part of an agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and the privately-funded <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> tests will set off 10 tons of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> 15 miles northeast of here and 100 miles north of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> today and another 10-ton blast tonight in <LOCATION> Lathrop </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wells </LOCATION>, 50 miles south of the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site. A 15-ton charge was to be detonated Saturday in <LOCATION> Broken </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Carson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The blasts will be monitored at three permanent centers surrounding the Test Site, including one in <LOCATION> Deep </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Bishop </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, where the Soviet technicians have installed a ton of their own scientific devices for the first time in this country. `` Typical underground nuclear explosions are measured in hundreds or thousands of tons of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION>,'' Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, senior staff scientist of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> told the news conference. `` By detonating only 10-15 tons, we will show that it is possible to detect very small explosions.'' By comparison, the bill passed in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday called for a ban on all underground nuclear explosions equivalent to more than 1,000 tons of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to do the same. One objection to a test ban has been that low-yield blasts could go virtually undetected, particularly if they were muffled in deep caverns. The equipment being used in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> is designed to be sophisticated enough `` to feel the difference between nuclear and industrial explosions and ... very small earthquakes,'' <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON> said. In addition to the equipment from the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Natura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Reno </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> are taking readings at 23 sites and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey has installed 120 seismometers and recorders along a line from the northwest corner of the state to its southern tip 450 miles away.
