<TEXT>
 A mentally retarded man who lived on <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>'s streets was convicted of first-degree murder in the death of another street person who was borderline mentally retarded. A jury delivered the verdict Thursday against <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, 30, after 13 hours of deliberation. The conviction carries a mandatory life sentence. The body of the victim, 33-year-old <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, was found in an alley a year ago. She had been suffocated. The two-week trial included testimony from about 50 people, including street people, neighborhood residents, social workers and police detectives. Among those testifying were people with mental disabilities who were on medication and had difficulty remembering events. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, said he will seek to get the verdict dismissed on the grounds that the evidence was insufficient to sustain a conviction.
