<HEAD>First-Ever Anglo-Soviet Drug Bust Nets 3.5 Tons of Hashish</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `He said ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with all
those arrested in Britain being British. PICKS up 5th graf, `The
spokesman ...' DELETES last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Customs investigators in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> seized 3.5 tons of Afghan hashish in the first-ever narcotics bust involving <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, authorities said today. `` The drugs came from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, overland through the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Soviet authorities got wind of that and agreed to cooperate in tracking them, letting them out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> so that we were able to seize them here,'' said Home Office Minister <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilley </PERSON>. Officers tracked the drugs from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital, by rail across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and by sea from <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Tilbury docks, said a Customs and Excise spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity He said five men, all British, were arrested Thursday night. It was not known whether the Soviets made any arrests on their own territory. The spokesman said the seizure, codenamed Operation Diplomat, arose from a visit by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last year. During the visit, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> and Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> discussed ways of cooperating against drugs. In July, officials from both countries got together to work out practical arrangements for fighting drug smuggling, and a memorandum of understanding was signed in February. Just before this, Soviet authorities intercepted the hashish, hidden in 400 sacks of liquorice root and packed in two containers. A <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> customs agent traveled to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and plans were made to find the drug traffickers. The Soviets agreed to let the containers continue their journey under surveillance. British investigators took over the watch when the containers left <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, and when they reached <LOCATION> Tilbury </LOCATION> a month ago the drugs were secretly removed from the cargo, which was then repacked and kept under observation, the spokesman said. Last Thursday, officers watched as the containers were collected from Tilbury and driven to a warehouse in an industrial zone on an abandoned <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Warrington </LOCATION>, northwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The load was then moved to storehouses in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and the customs investigators began making the arrests, the spokesman said.
