<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, despite a new emphasis on arms control initiatives and economic improvements, continues to build and modernize its military might in pursuit of an advantage over the West, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said today. Releasing its seventh annual assessment of Soviet forces, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported there were signs the military competition between the two superpowers would soon expand into new fields _ for example, the development of high-tech conventional weapons instead of nuclear arms. Indeed, the strategic nuclear balance `` is essentially stable,'' the report states. To date, however, `` we have seen no evidence of the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> changing the offensive nature of its force structure and deployment patterns,'' wrote <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> in a preface. `` Military output has not been reduced nor has military spending decreased. On the contrary, the Soviet military budget under General Secretary -LRB- <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> continues to grow at a rate of 3 percent per year at a level representing 15 to 17 percent of their GNP.'' By comparison, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending consumes about 6 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s GNP. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, appearing at a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> press confidence, cited several other developments, including the fact the Soviets now have two operational long-range nuclear missiles that use mobile launchers _ the SS-24 and the SS-25 _ while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has none. He also highlighted what he said was the first extensive, unclassified review of a Soviet program to construct underground bunkers, command centers and secret subways to protect their leaders in the event of a war. `` There can be only one purpose for these shelters _ to provide the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership the ability to fight a protracted, nuclear conflict,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> asserted. `` These facilities contradict in steel and concrete Soviet protestations that they share President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s view that nuclear war can never be won and must never be fought.'' But while Soviet military power is `` formidable,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> continued, `` we must not be overawed.'' `` Rather, we must strengthen our resolve to preserve our security and our freedoms. There is no mystery as to what <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> should do in the face of Soviet military power,'' he said. This year's review is the last to be prepared by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The 175-page glossy booklet differs substantially from the earlier reports in that it tries harder to gauge who's leading in various technologies and regions of the world, rather than just reporting what weapons have been added to the Soviet arsenal over the last year. Indeed, the report for the first time carries a subtitle: `` An Assessment of the Threat,'' and acknowledges that in areas such as naval power and high technology the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its Western allies still enjoy an advantage. The report does point to new weapon developments, though. Among them:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ The Soviets will soon deploy operational units of their new Blackjack long-range bomber Deployment of the new rail-mounted SS-24 nuclear missile has now begun, and production should start soon for a more accurate version of the huge SS-18 intercontinental ballistic missile, the mainstay of the Soviet arsenal. _ Production of self-propelled artillery pieces is at an `` all-time high;'' two new attack helicopters, the Havoc and Hokum, `` are expected to enter serial production soon,'' and the Soviets have begun fielding `` a new tank derived from the T-72, exhibiting improved protection, better mobility and enhanced firepower. _ <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> will complete a major upgrade of its anti-ballistic missile defense system protecting <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> `` in 1988 or 1989. A new `` Pill Box'' radar to help with tracking and targeting for that system is `` nearing completion at <LOCATION> Pushkino </LOCATION>.'' _ `` The Soviets are on the verge of deploying a variety of sophisticated cruise missile systems,'' and continue to lead the West in the pace of their activities in outer space. _ In the area of <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, is unlikely to develop small `` kinetic kill'' rockets that could be placed in space to shoot down nuclear missiles at long range The Soviets could, however, `` deploy a short-range, space-based system for space station defense or close-in attack by a maneuvering satellite in the near future.'' The report also spotlights for the first time Soviet efforts to develop the equipment needed for `` radio-electronic combat'' _ the use of electronic jamming and deception techniques to disrupt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and allied radio communication systems. On the strategic nuclear side, the report concludes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can deter a Soviet attack and continue to press for additional arms control agreements, so long as it continues President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s program of introducing weapons such as the B-1B and Stealth bombers and the MX missile while pursuing Star Wars research.
