<HEAD>U.S. Condemns Death of Imprisoned Czech Rights Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>, a human rights activist who died suddenly in a Czechoslovak jail, had asked the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> human rights conference to make sure he was not silenced in prison, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said today. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate to the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, condemned <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>'s imprisonment and said the conference had a `` special obligation to <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON> and to people like him.'' The conference adopted the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> accords on human rights in 1975. Prison authorities did not explain <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>'s death and official media in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> have not reported it. Human rights groups have said that the activist was beaten in detention. <PERSON> Frantiski </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolezel </PERSON>, the chief Czechoslovak delegate to the conference, said <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON> died of emphysema. `` As we record and mourn his untimely death, we must also condemn the wholly unjustifiable imprisonment and mistreatment he suffered while serving his term,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat said. <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>, who was released Feb. 26 after serving a 21-month prison sentence, was to be under `` protective surveillance'' for three years after he was freed. He was rearrested on April 5 and sentenced to another five-month jail term on unspecified charges April 21. <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> said that in his March 3 message, <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON> said people in the Soviet bloc should be made more aware of how their laws affect their rights and freedoms. `` My right to freedom of expression is guaranteed by the constitution of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Experience, however, has taught me not to depend too much on such declarations,'' <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON> as saying. `` Therefore, I have learned to be careful and I am taking the liberty to ask the ... governments of all the signatory states to see that my voice is not silenced _ under some pretext _ in prison,'' the message said. Several international groups have asked the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> government to allow independent doctors to attend <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>'s port-mortem. <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON>, an auto mechanic by profession, had sought to run for <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> as an independent candidate for his hometown in northern <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION>. He was known to be suffering from some intestinal problems but was not fatally ill, according to an emigre source.
