<HEAD>Tells Congress They Have `Limited Place' In Security Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who once threatened to resign if compelled to take a lie detector test, has authorized limited and voluntary use of polygraphs in <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> criminal and security investigations. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, in a statement he submitted Thursday to a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittee, sharply questioned the accuracy of such tests. `` It should never be acceptable in matters affecting the reputations and the livelihoods of individuals,'' he said. And yet, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` lie detector tests have a limited place in our security program'' in certain situations. He told the committee these included requests by <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> workers to establish their innocence and in criminal counterintelligence or personnel security investigations. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said a third circumstance for their use was when a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employee volunteered to work in an intelligence agency that required polygraph tests. But, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, the tests would be given only with the consent of the individual. `` It is no secret to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or to this committee that I have consistently opposed the use of lie detector tests as a tool for screening or managing people,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` Nor do I believe that we can single out one class of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employees for special treatment just because they are called a security service.'' He said the regulations in which he had authorized lie detector tests were `` clear, circumspect in scope and protect individual rights.'' In December 1985, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he would resign rather than be forced to take a polygraph test under a security program that had been ordered by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He called the tests inaccurate and unscientific. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> subsequently gave <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> discretion to decide whether polygraphs would be given in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
