<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has reached a tentative agreement with Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> under which he will resign as defense chief but remain on in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> for the time being, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said today. The official, insisting on anonymity, said the settlement is `` less than ideal'' because the administration had initially insisted that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> upon his resignation as part of a transition to democratic rule. `` We have to settle for three-fourths of a loaf,'' the official said. The administration had been concerned that any solution that allowed <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to remain on in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> could enable him to retain effective control even if he surrendered his post as commander of the Defense Forces. But the official said that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, once he steps down, would be like a `` cop out of uniform'' and would cease to be the dominant force in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political life. The timing of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s resignation and the question of whether he eventually will go into exile remain up in the air and are subject to future negotiations, the official said. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said in today's editions that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is known to prefer the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> if he is forced into exile. On Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> hinted that the admininistration was backing away from its demand that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> as part of a settlement. The administration goal, he said, was for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to `` leave power.'' <P