<HEAD>Court Invited to Consider Liability Issue Regarding Cheap Handguns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 2 grafs with further background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court today invited the District of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s highest court to consider whether gun manufacturers may be held liable in civil suits for deaths and injuries caused by cheap handguns. The advisory opinion was issued by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here about the dismissal of a civil suit against the manufacturer of the .22 - caliber pistol presidential assailant <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> used to shoot President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in It invited the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which interprets local law in the nation's capital, to determine whether to adopt a 1985 finding by <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s highest state court that gun manufacturers are liable for injuries and deaths caused by the criminal use of so-called Saturday Night Specials. The panel of three federal circuit judges found that the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> decision `` was based on public policy considerations'' expressed in that state's gun-control laws. `` The district's gun control statute ... places limitations on handgun ownership and purchases that are at least as strict as the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> provisions concerning handgun possession'' that formed the basis of the 1985 decision by <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s highest court, the panel said. `` Such a reassessment is permissive, not mandatory'' by the local appellate court, the federal panel said. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s legislature recently voted to outlaw all cheap handguns, but that change in policy should not be a factor in the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> court's review of the issue, the federal panel said in an opinion written by Circuit Judge <PERSON> Abner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikva </PERSON>. The advisory opinion follows by a year a decision by the same appellate court upholding the dismissal of <PERSON> Roehm </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as a defendant in civil suits filed by others wounded during <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s attack on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Roehm </PERSON>, which makes the guns through its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary R.G. Industries of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, had been sued for $ 20 million by White House press secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> police officer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Delahanty </PERSON>. Both were wounded along with <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Agent <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> when <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> shot <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on March 30, 1981. The shooting has left <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> confined to a wheelchair and <PERSON> Delahanty </PERSON>'s wounds forced him to retire from the police force. A suit against <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> by the three men is scheduled to go to trial May 16 in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Distict Court here. Two of the three judges in today's opinion, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, participated in last year's holding that gun manufacturers could not be held negligent for failing `` to prevent criminals from using their products.'' That decision also found that `` the strict liability claim fails because there is no allegation that the gun failed to operate properly. The gun was not defective.'' Because the 1987 opinion was not published by the court, it is not legal precedent. In a concurring opinion to today's ruling, <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> expressed regret that the court did not refer last year's issue for the same study by the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> court. <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> said that if the <ORGANIZATION> D.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> holds gun manufacturers can be sued, the federal appellate court can reconsider whether to reinstate the suits by <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <PERSON> Delahanty </PERSON> against <PERSON> Roehm </PERSON>. The court said that a review of the liability standard was appropriate because the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> was carved out of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and `` derived its common law from the state.'' The <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> decision, by a unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, also involved a lawsuit against <PERSON> Roehm </PERSON>. The state's highest court said the manufacturer or marketer of a Saturday Night Special knows or ought to know `` that he is making or selling a product principally to be used in criminal activity.'' These guns are `` largely unfit'' for legitimate uses, the court found.
