<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If imitation is the highest form of flattery, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s annual book on `` Soviet Military Power'' is basking in compliments. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has issued its own version, `` Whence the Threat to Peace.'' And <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, a critic of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, this spring published what he calls `` an annotated and corrected'' version of `` the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s propaganda document.'' Other military experts say that although the Pentagon book is not perfect, it is more accurate and comprehensive than either the Soviets' or <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>'s version. The latest edition, released by <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> today at a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> news conference, addresses some of the criticism by including more information and tables comparing <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact force levels, and acknowledging that the West leads in such areas as naval power and high technology. The latest, 175-page volume, which for the first time contains an index to weapons and photographs, reflects <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s desire for a more balanced and thorough approach. `` You'll note we have taken a somewhat different approach this year than in previous years. During my testimony -LRB- before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- earlier this year, I received a number of requests for an assessment of how Soviet military capabilities relate to our national interests, our military capabilities and those of our allies,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told the news conference. `` Furthermore, I believe it is especially important to share with the public as comprehensive a view of the trends and implications of Soviet military power as possible. And so this year the scope of the book has been expended ...'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` We welcome criticism.'' In September 1981, then-Defense Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> released the first edition of the book in a presentation beamed by satellite to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The administration was waging a campaign for a $ 1 trillion military buildup to close the gap on what he called Soviet military superiority. Although <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> billed the glossy, 99-page booklet as a compendium of `` scrubbed'' intelligence reports on Soviet defense, analysts outside government called it a rehash of information already available in public. The glossy book contained colorful maps, charts, photographs and artists' renditions of Soviet weaponry. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> published a Russian-language version, which diplomats in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> circulated among Soviet contacts. The Kremlin was not pleased. The Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda published a lengthy front-page editorial describing the Pentagon book as a `` big lie'' designed for `` simpletons.'' `` It is to be hoped that the foreign public will be able to judge the worth of the latest rotten fruit of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> propaganda,'' Pravda said on Oct. 17, 1981. By 1984, however, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> decided to weigh in with its own effort, `` Whence the Threat to Peace,'' drawing largely on Western publications to back Soviet claims that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was the chief instigator of the arms race. In his version issued this spring, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> author <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> was no less harsh than the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> wrote that in the Pentagon version, `` even the most basic facts are distorted'' as part of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration efforts to prove that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is on the losing end of a military gap. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>'s version includes the 1987 edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> book, overlaid with his own commentaries, for the most part corrections of the range and capabilities of Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> weaponry. `` In almost every case, the Americans have taken the lowest estimate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> capabilities and the highest for the Soviets,'' <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> said in his book and in a telephone interview. Military expert <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> says that <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, too, plays with the numbers. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, he says, `` believes that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, no matter what it's flaws, is never as bad as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He looks for any figure that shows a Soviet weapon to be less capable.'' For example, <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> says that the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> is incorrect in saying that the new Soviet 2-S-7 203mm howitzer has a range of 18 miles, and that instead it has a range of 10.8 miles. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>'s figure is for a 203mm gun made in 1931, rather than the latest Soviet version <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> noted that some of the artist's renditions appear to be wildly inaccurate, a claim that <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> says is justified in part. An early edition of the book carried a purported drawing of the Soviet T-80 tank, but it looked more like the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> M-1, said both <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>. Some of the Pentagon figures have been contradicted in testimony by administration officials on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, or by other authoritative works, says <PERSON> Isby </PERSON>, author of `` Weapons and Tactics of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` But generally, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> does a good job,'' <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Condoleeza </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, an expert on the Soviet military and professor at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, shares <PERSON> Isby </PERSON>'s assessment of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> book. `` I find it pretty useful, although from time to time, you find errors,'' she said in an interview. `` I find <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> a lot less useful. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> and <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> agreed that although the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> book has improved over the years, it still lacks a workable comparison of individual Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons, or overall forces. That issue probably can not be answered authoritatively as long as the superpowers disagree over who is ahead in the arms race.
