<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 12th graf, `I know ...', to UPDATE
with comment by Navy spokesman today on sequence of fire and
explosions. Picks up in 13th graf, `Following the ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As they waited for rescue, crewmen from the USS Bonefish refused to take a hovering helicopter's rescue line for themselves, passing it to their mates instead, a sailor from the ill-fated submarine said. `` They kept passing it feeling somebody would need it more than they. The first people we took were those who could n't swim well. Then we found we had some people who needed medical attention,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Bellows </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, the chief electrician's mate on the vessel <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> on Thursday said the crew members conducted an orderly evacuation of the ship through thick, poisonous smoke after a fire and explosions damaged the diesel-electric submarine. Three crewmen were killed in Sunday's accident while 22 others from the 92-man crew suffered smoke inhalation. Two remained hospitalized in satisfactory condition Thursday. The 219-foot Bonefish was involved in maneuvers off the coast of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> at the time of the fire. <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> said the three dead men were were relatively new to the boat and may have been doomed by their unfamiliarity with its layout. Officials at the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> fleet headquarters in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, say the first explosion took place in the submarine's forward battery compartment while the vessel was cruising at periscope depth. The batteries are used to power the sub when it is below the surface, and recharging them generates hydrogen gas, which can explode if allowed to accumulate. However, <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> said a fire initially broke out in the crew living quarters but apparently could n't be contained. `` They had this small fire in berthing and a couple of people manned fire extinguishers and attempted to put it out,'' he said. Initial reports that the fire was under control were followed by reports it was spreading, he said. `` From everybody I talked to there was an explosion later, maybe five minutes down the road,'' he said. He said `` there's a lot of anger among the crew'' over speculation in the media that high levels of hydrogen in the battery compartments may have caused the explosions. `` I know for a fact we had zero percent hydrogen in the battery well,'' he said. Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Borton </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, said today the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had no comment on the sequence of fire and explosions aboard the Bonefish. Following the explosions, the Bonefish surfaced and its captain, Cmdr. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, ordered the crew evacuated to the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and frigate USS Carr, which were nearby. No one was available for comment on <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s account, an officer at fleet headquarters said Thursday night. Telephone calls to four spokesmen at home went unanswered or were not returend. The Bonefish was expected to arrive in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, its homeport, by early afternoon, said Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mowery </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> prepared for a memorial service Saturday for the crewmen who died. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said the remains of Lt. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Everts </PERSON>, 30, of <LOCATION> Naoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, Petty Officer 1st Class <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bordelow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 39, of <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and Petty Officer 3rd Class <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindgren </PERSON>, 21, of <ORGANIZATION> Pisgah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, had been removed from the vessel and flown to the <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>
