<SECOND>PM-Copyright Treaty,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Copyright Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters today predicted swift House action on a bill allowing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to adhere to a century-old international copyright treaty and strengthen its hand against foreign piracy of records, tapes and computer technology. The measure was approved Thursday by a voice vote of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> without the so-called `` moral rights'' provision sought by <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> film makers to help prevent unauthorized coloring and other alterations in works sold to television broadcasters. Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kastenmeier </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., chief sponsor of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, said the moral rights issue will be considered later in separate hearings by his Judiciary subcommittee, which considers copyright issues A similar measure, also without a moral rights provision, was approved April 14 by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Approval of the legislation by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was expected within the next few weeks, congressional staff aides said. If the treaty is then ratified by a two-thirds majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would join 76 other nations that subscribe to the <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION> Convention for the <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artistic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>, which sets the world standard for copyright protection of creative works exported by any of the signatory nations. <PERSON> Kastenmeier </PERSON> and other supporters of the bill said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> adherence would help stem piracy of American-owned works in the computer and entertainment fields. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers of records and tapes, for example, lost an estimated $ 558 million in sales in 1986 because of foreign counterfeiting and piracy, according to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` I want to bring this to the full House for a vote right away,'' <PERSON> Kastenmeier </PERSON> said today through a spokeswoman. `` Every day the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waits to join <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION> is another day that the gold medalist of the world intellectual property Olympics stays on the bench for lack of proper credentials.'' <PERSON> Kastenmeier </PERSON> said the bill would allow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to improve copyright relations with 24 of the 76 subscribing nations. `` Joining the <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION> convention is a trade issue as well as an artistic concern,'' he said. `` ... We enhance our own political credibility in our global efforts to raise copyright standards and reduce piracy. The more we achieve in all those areas, the better we protect American jobs and American creativity.'' At a hearing before a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on March 3, film makers <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> appealed for a statutory `` moral rights'' ban on changes in a motion picture by its financial backers or buyers without the consent of directors and screenwriters. `` American law does not protect our painters, sculptors, recording artists, authors or film makers from having their life work distorted and their reputation distorted,'' said <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, who directed the hit movie `` Star Wars.''
</TEXT>
