pvs, Baker reminded.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s senior aides apparently got the message when Chief of Staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told them he will not tolerate attempts to undermine Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, the president's spokesman said today. An administration source said earlier that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told subordinates Thursday he had `` had it'' with a spate of news stories about underground efforts to win <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s ouster. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> reminded aides that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has repeatedly stated his confidence in <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, and told them `` those people who disagree with that should come to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and talk,'' said the source, speaking on grounds he not be identified publicly. He said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> left no doubt that such a meeting would center on the continuing job status of the complaining aide. Spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said he did not believe anybody had been in to see <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> as a result of his comments. `` I do n't think anybody missed the message,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` They'd be too dumb to work at the White house if they did.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> reminded aides that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has repeatedly stated his confidence in <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, and told them `` those people who disagree with that should come to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and talk,'' said the source, speaking on grounds he not be identified publicly. He said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> left no doubt that such a meeting would center on the continuing job status of the complaining aide. The source said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> made it clear that because <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> still has confidence in <LOCATION> Meese </LOCATION>, his staff should respect that. He said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told aides that he, too, believes in <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s innocence. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> has been examining <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s assistance to the scandal-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and a proposed $ 1 billion oil pipeline project Also under investigation are <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s meetings with regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> telephone company executives at a time when he owned $ 14,000 in <ORGANIZATION> Baby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> stock In addition, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> is looking into the $ 40,000-a-year job for the attorney general's wife, <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, that is being funded by the foundation of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> family that has leased real estate to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> The administration source said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was not directly challenged by anyone in the meeting. `` You should have seen all the heads at the table, nodding up and down, and probably someone at that table had been leaking stories,'' he said. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, asked about <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s threat, said, `` Senator <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told the senior staff that the president supports <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> supports <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and if anybody questions that policy, then they should n't. Asked whether <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a former senator from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, had suggested that those in disagreement might leave the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>