<HEAD>Talks Continue Amid Mutual Distrust</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with one graf to UPDATE with talks resuming. Pick up
2nd pvs, `The two...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government and rebel leaders began a second day of meetings today in a climate of mutual distrust, having made little apparent headway in talks on achieving a lasting peace. The two delegations ended their closed-door session Thursday night with neither side offering comment on what progress, if any, had been made. Defense Minister <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> started the meeting by calling for a 30-day extention to the 60-day truce that ends June 1. The U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, rejected the proposal. Contra leaders arrived Thursday for a second three-day round of high-level meetings to work out details of the cease-fire agreement they signed with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government March 23 in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. The two sides have agreed on little since signing the preliminary peace accord, which aims to end the 6 -LCB- - year-old war that has claimed more than 26,000 lives In a surprise move, the government announced Thursday that the Contras may receive immediate humanitarian aid if it is distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. The Sapoa accord calls for humanitarian aid to be provided to the rebels only after they gather in seven mutually agreed cease-fire zones. `` It is an effort to ease the pacification process that restores peace and the possibility of national reconciliation,'' Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> told journalists. Under the accords, the rebels were to have moved into the zones two weeks ago, but the two sides have been unable to define the security and operating conditions within the zones. Many Contra fighters have moved into the general areas of the zones over the last few weeks. But journalists traveling to the isolated regions said the combatants are wary of the pact. The Sandinista proposal calls on the Contras to lay down their arms, an issue not specifically mentioned in the Sapoa accords. `` We insist that first we should discuss and reach an agreement about the modus operandi'' within the zones, said Contra leader <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>. He said that to accept the government's proposal would be tantamount to surrender. The government says the laying down of arms is basic to the agreement _ but the Contras say they will do so only when <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is on `` the irreversible road to democracy.'' The two sides met Thursday at the Camino Real Hotel near the airport. The Contras are isolated from contact with the general public, but are permitted to make brief forays to speak to waiting journalists at a nearby hotel. The Contras' first three days of high-level talks in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> began April 15 and netted nothing more than an agreement to meet again.
