<HEAD>Partisan Squabbling Derails Sanctions Bill in House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Efforts by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats to advance a sweeping South African sanctions bill were derailed Friday when partisan squabbling broke out in the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the measure became entangled with a separate bill on <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. The legislation would cut off virtually all economic relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> within a year. It is seen by supporters as building upon the limited sanctions imposed two years ago to force <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> to moderate its apartheid policy, which deprives majority blacks of political and civil rights. But the measure is opposed by business interests as too harsh to have its intended effect, and many Republicans who supported limited sanctions in 1986 have said they will fight the Democrats this time. Rep. <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, had planned to begin work on the sanctions bill Friday He was forced to postpone his panel's meeting until next week, however, after the measure became entangled in a dispute about a separate, Republican-sponsored bill to condemn the Marxist government of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. `` I guess it reflects some of the rising political tensions'' of this election year, said Rep. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, D-Ind., a senior committee member Republicans were holding up the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> sanctions bill as leverage to first force action on the Ethiopian measure. That bill urges President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to cut off imports of Ethiopian coffee and deny trade preferences if the Soviet-aligned government continues to impede relief efforts for starving people in its northern provinces. Ethiopian President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> on April 6 ordered foreign relief workers out of the provinces of <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, where his forces are at war with secessionist rebels. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> has been accused of trying to starve his own people into submission, and more than 2 million people are reported to be at risk of starvation. The <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> sanctions measure, sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., was to have been acted on Friday before the committee turned to consideration of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> sanctions bill But Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, D-Wash., objected, saying the measure was poorly written and was being rushed through without proper referral to the trade subcommittee, which he heads As the committee's meeting hit impasse and broke up, Republicans cried foul. `` It's a sad mark of politics and procedure,'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said. `` We've got millions of people starving to death.'' He accused <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, who is running for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in his forestry-oriented state, of trying to use the situation to advance a pet bill imposing restrictions on exports of unprocessed logs. <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON> had told reporters that bill might come before the full <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> this week, but that did not happen. <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON> denied any connection between the two bills. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>, R-Ind., said he would continue to use House rules to block consideration of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> bill until the Democratic-controlled committee acts on <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> sanctions `` The Ethiopian bill is much more significant at this point that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' he said. But one Democrat said the Republicans were merely using every tactic they could to delay further action on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which Democrats see as a potent political issue in their favor. `` When you're looking to sidetrack an issue, your best bet is to light forest fires all around the place,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` It's a testy time.''
