frica </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, is ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in defiance of a 1966 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> demand to give it independence. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said it is willing to give <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence, but insists <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> withdraw its estimated 40,000 troops from neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has been trying for nine years to mediate an agreement, backs <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s demand that the first move be a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> demands that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stop backing pro-Western rebels fighting to overthrow its Marxist government. It says <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has 9,000 troops with heavy artillery in Angolan territory, while <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says it has not had more than 3,000 men there at one time since May 1987. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has been waging a 21-year war with Namibian independence fighters based in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, while <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> has been wracked by civil war since 1975. <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s ally in the Angolan civil war, got <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid worth $ 15 million last year, including Stinger anti-aircraft missiles. In the past few months, most of the heavy fighting has been around the strategic southeastern city of Cuito Cuanavale. Cu