<HEAD>Arrest Of Underground Preacher Belies Relaxed Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The apparent arrest of an underground Christian preacher comes during a time of unusual tolerance by the Communist government toward <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s illegal `` house churches.'' Another underground minister in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> said authorities recently have not stopped him and other preachers from holding weekly services in their homes for dozens and even hundreds of people even though they violate <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ban on preaching outside state-sanctioned churches. The minister, who spoke on condition of anonymity, painted a picture of an underground movement toughened by past harsh repression and confident it can survive any setbacks. `` I was in prison more than 20 years _ I'm experienced,'' the 74-year-old minister said grinning broadly. `` If I am arrested again and die for the Lord it is glorious.'' He and <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yongzhe </PERSON>, who disappeared April 16 and is believed to have been arrested, are among thousands of <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> ministers and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priests and nuns who refuse to join the official churches. Instead, they preach at home. About 8 million people belong to the official <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> churches in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and nearly as many are believed to belong to the house churches. The believers make up a tiny fraction of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s more than 1 billion people. Although some house church preachers and members remain in prisons and labor camps _ the minister said there were 500 in custody _ the government is more tolerant of their activities than ever before in nearly four decades of Communist rule. The minister said authorities have not bothered him even though he remains under probation after being freed from jail in 1979, and holds two services each Sunday. Forty people crowd into his one-room home _ something impossible to hide from neighbors in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s tightly packed residential areas. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s arrest, however, was no surprise. He had been a fugitive since 1982, when he escaped from a jail in <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, hopped on a bicycle and peddled into hiding. He ran an underground seminary but was not especially prominent among house church preachers, his fellow minister said. Xu, believed to be about 50, had been in jail only a few months charged with illegal proselytizing. The other minister said he did not know <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s sentence. He said he'd been expecting <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> to visit the day he disappeared. Instead, <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s sister came alone and reported that <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> disappeared while visiting the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Zoo with two friends, the second day after he left his hiding place in northern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to hear visiting <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> preach in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. He said <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s sister received no confirmation from authorities that he had been arrested, but it appeared certain. The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> refused to answer queries about Xu. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said Friday in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> at the end of his 16-day Chinese tour that he asked high-level Chinese officials about the reported arrest but received neither confirmation nor denial. The renowned Southern Baptist minister said he prayed for <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> and told Chinese officials his reaction to the report, but could not otherwise intervene. `` Our hope is from the Lord, not from <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s colleague said The minister said he studied theology under Western missionaries in the 1930s, but <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> and younger house preachers learned through self-study and informal training by house church preachers. Funds and thousands of Bibles are smuggled in each year from religious groups outside <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The minister said the house churches have no central organization and do not oppose the government. `` We have no time to mess with the things of the world,'' he said. `` I believe politics and religion should be separate. The -LRB- official -RRB- churches have become a tool of the government. They preach to ... serve the modernization policy.'' Indeed, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Catholic church does not recognize the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. During the 1966-76 far leftist Cultural Revolution all churches were closed and religious activity was banned. Although some churches have been reopened since <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> came to power in 1978, ministers and priests are closely circumscribed. They can not give religious instruction to anyone under 18, and must support government campaigns. Preaching on themes such as diligence, honesty and respect for parents is considered to have social value. But the Christian belief that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> will come again at the end of the world is discouraged as likely to undermine hard work. `` We are free _ but only inside the circle,'' the minister said, running a finger around the rim of a rice bowl in illustration.
