<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Book,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci Puts Moderate Stamp On Latest Edition Of Soviet Arms
Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Military Power Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new defense secretary, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, on Friday put his own moderate stamp on the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s annnual review `` Soviet Military Power.'' The book has generated a host of critics and at least two imitations since then-Defense Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> issued the first edition in 1981, at the outset of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's $ 1 trillion defense buildup. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has its own version, `` Whence the Threat to Peace.'' And <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, a critic of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, this spring published what he calls `` an annotated and corrected'' version of `` the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s propaganda document.'' Now austerity has put a crimp in the Pentagon budget, and time and <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> have removed some of the book's more jagged edges. Early editions of `` Soviet Military Power'' drew criticism from many analysts on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> and outside government because of alleged innaccuracies and failure to compare overall capabilities of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact and the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The 1988 edition released at a news conference on Friday, the first since <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> became replaced <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> as defense secretary last Nov. 5, addresses those criticisms by including more comparative text and graphs. It also acknowledges that the West leads in such areas as naval power and high technology. The book has shed the warlike red cover of previous years in favor of calmer gray background and a photograph of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on the deck of a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Typhoon </LOCATION> nuclear ballistic missile submarine. Also, the publication devotes most of its first 30 pages to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s overall national security policy before turning to military spending and hardware. `` You'll note we have taken a somewhat different approach this year than in previous years,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told reporters. `` During my testimony -LRB- before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- earlier this year, I received a number of requests for an assessment of how Soviet military capabilities relate to our national interests, our military capabilities and those of our allies,'' he said. `` Furthermore, I believe it is especially important to share with the public as comprehensive a view of the trends and implications of Soviet military power as possible. And so this year the scope of the book has been expanded ...'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` We welcome criticism.'' The latest 175-page volume is nearly double the 99 pages of the first edition, and for the first time contains an index to weapons and photographs. In 1981 <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>, in a presentation beamed by satellite to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, issued the first edition together with a declaration that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was stronger militarily than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> billed the book as a compendium of `` scrubbed'' intelligence reports on Soviet defense, but analysts outside government called it a rehash of information already available publicly. It contained colorful maps, charts, photographs and artists' renditions of Soviet weaponry The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> published a Russian-language version, which diplomats in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> circulated among Soviet contacts. The Kremlin was not pleased. The Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda published a lengthy front-page editorial describing the Pentagon book as a `` big lie'' designed for `` simpletons.'' `` It is to be hoped that the foreign public will be able to judge the worth of the latest rotten fruit of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> propaganda,'' Pravda said on Oct. 17, 1981. A few years later, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> weighed in with its own effort, `` Whence the Threat to Peace,'' drawing largely on Western publications to back Soviet claims that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was the chief instigator of the arms race. In his version issued this spring, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> author <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> was no less harsh than the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> wrote that in editions as recent as last year, `` even the most basic facts are distorted'' as part of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration efforts to prove that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is on the losing end of a military gap. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>'s version includes the 1987 edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> book, overlaid with his own commentaries, in large part corrections of the range and capabilities of Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> weaponry. `` In almost every case, the Americans have taken the lowest estimate for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> capabilities and the highest for the Soviets,'' <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON> said in his book and in a telephone interview. Military expert <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Isby </PERSON> says that <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, too, plays with the numbers. <PERSON> Gervasi </PERSON>, he said, `` believes that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, no matter what its flaws, is never as bad as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He looks for any figure that shows a Soviet weapon to be less capable.''
