<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of employees struck for higher pay at a heavy machinery plant Friday, capping a week of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor trouble since the Communist authorities suppressed Solidarity more than six years ago <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> police detained <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, a senior adviser to the outlawed union. A member of his household said three plainclothesmen arrived as <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> was being interviewed by telephone by a Western radio station. Strikes began Monday with bus and streetcar drivers at <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> in the west. Workers at the huge <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> steel works at <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> in the southern industrial belt followed suit Tuesday, and on Friday it was the machinery plant at <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, about 65 miles east of <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>. Another job action was threatened for over the May Day holiday weekend. Solidarity activists in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s municipal transport company said in a statement they were calling a strike for 6 a.m. Saturday to support the <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> workers. Workers demand pay increases of 50 percent or more. Prices rose 42 percent in the first three months of 1988 because the government reduced subsidies on many consumer items. The government has both threatened dismissals and promised to improve wages. At <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION>, the 2,800 drivers won a 60 percent pay increase with an 11-hour strike. Officials of Solidarity threatened more strikes if authorities use force against strikers. They said workers in at least four other cities had declared support for the Nowa Huta action and issued strike alerts. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Bild </ORGANIZATION> quoted Solidarity founder <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> as saying in an interview the strike `` has to spread because the economic situation is bad. We really did n't want to strike because strikes have never filled a bread basket, but the government leaves us no choice but to fight for our rights.'' Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said an attempt to start a strike failed at the 18,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Stalowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wola </ORGANIZATION> heavy machinery plant, but the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said later at least one department was shut down. A Roman Catholic priest in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, the Rev. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemiec </PERSON>, said about 7,000 strikers were occupying three department and the strike began when about 5,000 first-shift employees quit working. He said management tried to lock out most of the second-shift workers but some broke in. <PERSON> Niemiec </PERSON> said the number of strikers could be as high as 9,000, but he could not confirm the figure. He said the information came from a member of the strike committee. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, strikers customarily go to their places of employment but do not work. Often they hold meetings or pass out leaflets. About 12,000 workers were striking for a fourth day at the Lenin plant in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, which means <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mill </ORGANIZATION> and was built as a model city in the 1950s just outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. Management representatives met with the plant's government-sanctioned union but refused to deal with the unofficial committee that claims to represent at least half the plant's 32,000 workers The <ORGANIZATION> Nowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huta </ORGANIZATION> strike is the biggfest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since those that swept the country after food price increases in 1980, bringing down a government and giving birth to Solidarity. The independent union federation was suppressed, then outlawed, after martial law was declared in December 1981. Urban said there had been `` preventative detentions'' in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> this week, but did not say how many. <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, the Solidarity adviser, said by telephone before his detention that 25 people had been picked up around the country in the past two days. <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, an adviser to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, said police stopped his car Thursday in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> and detained him, Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON> remained in custody. <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON>, a Solidarity spokesman in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, said many police were in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> and at least four Solidarity activists were detained. Demands at <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> are representative: recognition of their union rights, release of detained Solidarity activists and an immediate 50 percent increase in monthly pay that averages the equivalent of $ 105. The strike committee said it had sent a letter to <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, who was <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s archbishop before becoming pope, that began: `` We address you with our words of devotion and respect. We are sending those words from the place of our work and struggle for decent payment.'' Urban told a news conference in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>: `` The situation in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is not dramatic, with only one strike in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> and an attempt to organize a strike that failed in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> Nowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huta </ORGANIZATION> management had decided to fire striking workers. Labor Minister <PERSON> Ireneneusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sekula </PERSON> said the government would announce tax law changes and other measures in a few days allowing enterprises to grant higher pay. He said he could not be more specific. <PERSON> Trybuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludu </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, attacked `` Mr. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and company ... who are trying to use the uneasy situation for their own political goals.'' It said demands for higher wages were `` calls for anarchy, to start unrestrained inflation, to create a situation in which we would once again have empty store shelves and the creditors would lose their growing confidence in us.''
