<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Diplomats     04-29 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Diplomats,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unpaid Parking Fines Down Sharply After Britain Gets Tough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new government policy that threatens to turn diplomats' unpaid parking tickets into airplane tickets expelling them from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has foreign envoys rushing to pay their fines. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that 18,000-member diplomatic community ran up only 14,437 unpaid fines last year, compared with 108,845 in 1984. Foreign Office Minister <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Eggar </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in a written statement that the number was down 35 percent from 1986. Diplomats, under international conventions, are immune from prosecution for offenses committed in the host country, but the host can have the offender expelled. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> says that in 1985 it began issuing expulsion threats against repeat parking offenders, but has not yet ordered anyone out. It said it sent out a dozen such warnings last year. Many diplomats complain they have to park illegally because their missions are in the congested heart of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, with 799 unpaid fines, topped <PERSON> Eggar </PERSON>'s list. Rounding out the top five were the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with 622, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with 551, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> with 513 and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> with 435. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and 10 countries had no fines unpaid last year: <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> had 77 unpaid fines, only 17 of them in the second half of the year. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> had 130, including 36 in the second half. `` We decided in 1985 that we were going to take a very tough line and insist that diplomats paid their fines,'' <PERSON> Eggar </PERSON> told a reporter. `` We ca n't force them to pay,'' he said, `` but we regard it as an abuse of diplomatic immunity, and we make it quite clear that, if they are persistent offenders and they do n't pay, they ca n't stay in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>. The Foreign Office has no figures for fines paid, but <PERSON> Eggar </PERSON> said: `` Up to 1984, the number of unpaid fines was rising dramatically. It is now falling even more dramatically.'' He said he would thank missions which pay their fines, and demand improvements from those that do n't. He added he was confident that all British diplomats abroad paid their fines. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> of the city's Commission for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Consular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> said British diplomats do have outstanding, unpaid parking tickets and, like most nations' diplomats, generally do not pay them But, he added, British diplomats get relatively few tickets. `` They have one of the best records for violations per vehicle,'' he said. In another Commons reply, <PERSON> Eggar </PERSON> reported 43 alleged `` serious offenses'' by foreign diplomats in 1987, resulting in 18 diplomats being ousted. The offenses included 26 cases of drunken driving, 13 of theft and shoplifting, and one each of forgery, driving without insurance, possession of drugs and indecent assault.
</TEXT>
