<HEAD>Judge Moves To Free Multiple Personality Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge ruled Friday that a man found innocent by reason of insanity on rape charges because he had multiple personalities is now well, apparently clearing the way for his release. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> has been confined in various mental institutions around the state for much of the time since the original ruling in 1977. Judge <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said psychiatric and psychological reports show <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>'s multiple personalities have fused, and that he is well. <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>, who was charged with rape and abduction in three attacks in the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> area, once had more than 20 personalities, according to the book `` The Minds of <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>.'' As a result of the judge's ruling, <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> was transferred from the maximum security section of the <ORGANIZATION> Timothy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moritz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forensics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here to the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> had been confined at the <PERSON> Moritz </PERSON> center since he was captured in December 1986 after escaping from the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> on July 4, 1986. Officials say it will take about a month to place him in private housing and help him try to find a job. During his court appearance Friday, <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> pledged to obey the law and said he wants to be a tax-paying citizen. He said he wants to continue his work as an artist, or find a job involving computers. <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> still must undergo therapy twice a week for the next year, according to the judge's ruling. <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> also was charged in a November 1984 shooting at a barn on property owned by a worker at a mental health facility where he was a patient. No one was injured in the shooting, and the case was dismissed after defense attorneys claimed that <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>'s constitutional rights were violated when a jailer recorded his side of a phone conversation with his attorney.
