<HEAD>Sikhs Militants Attack Troops Outside Temple; 24 Dead Throughout
Punjab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh militants holed up in the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> attacked para-military troops on Friday and at least 24 people were killed in other parts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> in separatist violence, police and news reports said. The slayings raised to 862 the number of people killed this year in attacks blamed on the radical movement for a Sikh homeland. At least six people were killed and 80 injured when five bombs exploded on Friday afternoon in the crowded main market of <LOCATION> Batala </LOCATION> town, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. It said police clamped an indefinite curfew on the town, 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, after the explosions. At least two of the victims were reported to be militants. Three people who were believed to have placed the explosives were arrested, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. Merchants around <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine, closed their shops when militants fired at a patrol of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, said police superintendent <PERSON> Baldev </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>. The attack started when the troops attempted to arrest a wanted militant as he was heading for the shrine, <PERSON> Baldev </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said. The troops returned the fire but the militant escaped in the confusion. One woman was injured in the 20-minute firefight, he said. The attack prompted authorities to place the city's police force on a `` red alert'' although security forces did not attempt to enter the temple. Security forces have entered the temple previously but usually avoid doing so because of Sikh sentiment. Police estimate that at least 100 militants, armed with automatic rifles, are hiding in the shrine. In other militant attacks Thursday night, at least seven Hindus were shot and killed in two villages near <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. Five Sikhs were killed in a raid on a farmer's home, also near <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. At least six other people, including four Sikhs and two unidentified victims, were shot and killed in other attacks through the state. Sikhs form 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but make up a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The militants have been agitating for an independent homeland since 1983, claiming discrimination by the Hindu majority.
