<HEAD>Soviet Departure Will Revive Old Rivalries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast; picks up 3d `The patchwork'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet presence has wrought little change in this city of dusty streets and mud huts, but hatred of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> forged an alliance among tribal enemies that lasted 10 years. Whether the Moslem guerrillas will revel in their rout of the Soviets after the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> leaves or press on with the fight to oust President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his Communist government is an open question. The patchwork of tribes and nationalities that joined forces, more or less, after the Communist coup in April 1978 have a much longer history of strife and infighting. Few of the merchants, farmers, students and government workers biding their time in the relatively safe capital display much emotion when asked what they expect to happen when the 115,000 Soviet soldiers are gone. Few hold out much hope for <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, a former head of the secret police chosen by the Kremlin two years ago to President <PERSON> Babrak </PERSON> <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON>. The Soviet military forces are to begin leaving by May 15 and be out in nine months. Equally few expect a unified opposition to emerge. For ordinary Afghans, replacing the peril and loss of the civil war with the familiar troubles of the past would be welcome. `` <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> has always had problems,'' a young taxi driver observed in broken English. `` What will happen after the Russians leave, we will see.'' Dislike of the Soviets and nostalgia for the monarchy ousted by the military 15 years ago are strong among Afghan civilians. They seem eager to return to their former lives, when battles were as numerous but dealt with land and water instead of ideology. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Mir </PERSON>, an English-speaking antique dealer who parks his blue Mercedes outside a cluttered shop on Chicken Street, says business is good despite the war, but he would be happy to leave it all behind for his native city of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>. `` My house there was destroyed twice, so we came to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'' in the 1970s, he said. The attackers were a neighboring tribe that coveted his fertile land, not political opponent. Mir said he would like to see the king return and the Soviets leave. `` I do n't do business with the Russian dogs,'' he told an American visitor. `` I send them to the Indian next door.'' Just then, three Soviet soldiers with automatic rifles passed the shop, looking uncomfortable as they patrolled the shopping street. At the <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> market, a warren of low-roofed hovels in central <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> named for the late Soviet leader, there is a brisk trade in Soviet machinery and spare parts. One merchant said he would leave soon for his home in western <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> because Soviet troops there were packing up to leave. How will he make a living after a decade of dealing in Soviet hardware? He shrugged and said: `` We made our business in other ways before the Soviets came and we will make it in other ways when they leave.'' About 2 million people live in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. It crouches in dun-colored poverty in a broad basin ringed by high mountains, which the guerrillas control. Women wearing full-length pleated silk veils sort onions, carrots and geens for sale in their market stalls, as others did for generations before the Soviets came. Crowds of shoppers and traders throng the narrow walkways between open troughs carrying waste water. The smell of raw sewage from the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> mingles with exotic scents from the spice shops. Rocket fire occasionally reaches the city from the mountains. Car bombs have become more frequent, like the one that killed six passersby and wounded 49 other people on Wednesday, the 10th anniversary of the Communist coup. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Masum </PERSON> said he believes fewer than 20 percent of Afghans are concerned with politics and even he, a member of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s party, is ready to cope with whatever political situation develops. He and other Afghans are just tired of war. `` I think if there was a true coalition government, including the king, we would all be happy,'' <PERSON> Masud </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> has offered the guerrillas a coalition but they have refused. At a news conference Thursday he suggested a role in the government for former King <PERSON> Sahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, but did not say what it would be. `` I just want to go to my home as soon as they will let me,'' said <PERSON> Masum </PERSON>, an interpreter with the party <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION>, Solidarity and Friendship. He and his wife fled their village outside <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in the early days of the war. `` I'm not afraid of either side,'' he said. `` Now I interpret for the government. Maybe later I will interpret for someone else.''
