<HEAD>No Breakthrough In Sight For Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 40-nation <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disarmament </ORGANIZATION> wound up its spring session Friday with no breakthrough in sight on a global ban on chemical weapons even though many delegates agree the ban is more urgent than ever. Negotiations on a convention prohibiting the development, production, and stockpiling of chemical weapons and providing for their destruction dominated the three-month meeting. However, early pronouncements that a text could be finalized this year clashed with the reality of the complexities involved, delegates said. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Meiszter </PERSON>, president of the conference for April, told a press conference that he was optimistic that agreement will come `` in the near future.'' But other conference sources, while acknowledging further progress, simply said many unresolved problems make any predictions impossible. At the same time, addresses to the conference have stressed that the continued use of chemical weapons in the war between <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have added urgency to the 20-year-old negotiations. The latest addition to the potential stumbling blocks is <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s insistence on provisions allowing `` security stocks'' of chemical weapons for eight years after the convention enters into force. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> argues that such a possibility is needed in view of the `` very large disproportion'' between existing chemical stocks. This is an evident reference to the Soviet arsenal. The Soviets say they have 50,000 tons of chemical weapons, but Western intelligence sources say that is a gross understatement. Obsolete <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chemical weapons stockpiled in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> are to be removed in 1992 under an informal understanding between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>. This would leave the Soviets with the only chemical weapons left on <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> territory. Diplomatic sources who insisted on anonymity said no other delegation supports the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> proposal because in effect it would give countries that do not have chemical weapons the go-ahead to start production of the arms the moment the convention is ratified. `` It is the top issue now,'' said one Western source. `` I ca n't see any treaty if <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> sticks to its position. The chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative, ambassador <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON>, was quoted in an interview as saying that the negotiations are getting to the point `` where we are going to have one -LRB- a ban -RRB- or not going to have one.'' <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said the problems with the treaty range from details of anti-cheating provisions to monitoring the civilian industry to make surce that chemicals are not diverted to hostile uses. The interview was printed in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mission's Daily Bulletin. It did not include any mention of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> proposal. Up to now, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are the only member countries that have admitted possession of chemical weapons. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not officially disclosed its reserves but they are generally reported to total less than 30,000 tons. Western sources estimate at least 15 other countries may have chemical weapons.
