<TEXT>
 A medical team plans a marathon, high-risk operation to separate 16-month-old Siamese twins joined at the head, doctors said Friday. Doctors at <LOCATION> Baragwanath </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, the main hospital in the black township outside <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, performed two preliminary operations in October in preparation for Tuesday's surgery. The procedure is expected to take at least nine hours. The twin girls, <PERSON> Mpho </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mphonyana </PERSON>, were born Dec. 7, 1986, to <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON>, an unmarried, 33-year-old black domestic worker who earns about $ 60 a month. The girls share a major blood vessel in their heads. Doctors partially clamped the vein in the earlier operations in hopes that lesser blood vessels would take over its functions. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipschitz </PERSON>, head of the medical team, said the chances for success were not high, but that doctors would not sacrifice one of the girls to save the other. `` This is going to be a long, lengthy, intricate operation which carries many dangers with it,'' <PERSON> Lipschitz </PERSON> told a news conference Friday. `` The prognosis is still very grave.'' `` Though the chances are still not in both the children's favor, at this moment they appear to stand the best chance that we can give them under the present state of the art,'' he said. The girls have a combined weight of 33 pounds. <PERSON> Mpho </PERSON> appears to be developing normally and recently began to speak, while <PERSON> Mphonyana </PERSON> is slightly smaller and does not appear to be as advanced, the hospital said. The Baragwanath doctors have received advice from <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, where in September doctors separated West German twins joined at the head. Both boys survived and were sent home in March, but they reportedly are suffering physical and mental problems. Ms. <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON> was asked to make a $ 5 contribution to the costs of the operation, which otherwise are being covered by the hospital and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> medical school.
