<HEAD>Louvre Has Successful Fund-Raiser to Buy Masterpiece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fund drive has raised most of the $ 5.6 million needed to buy a 17th century masterpiece by <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Tour </PERSON>, and the government said Friday it will provide the rest so the painting will remain in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The austere portrait `` St. Thomas'' is the last work of de la Tour -LRB- 1593-1652 -RRB- still in private hands. With the campaign closing Saturday, about $ 4.2 million of the necessary 32 million has been raised from bequests, corporations and visitors to the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>. The final contribution from <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> will allow the Louvre to buy the painting from the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, an international charity group founded in the 11th century. It has been on show at the <LOCATION> Jeu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paume </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION> annex, since the campaign began March 22 and has attracted thousands of visitors, many of whom put dropped modest donations into the tall black urn at the entrance, said <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sylvie </PERSON> <PERSON> Poujade </PERSON>. When the fund drive began, Finance Minister <PERSON> Eduoard </PERSON> <PERSON> Balladur </PERSON> said the government would pay a substantial share to keep the painting in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Ministry officials confirmed Friday that state funds would put the campaign over the top. The Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> acquired the painting in 1985 in the will of <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruille </PERSON>, an unmarried countess who lived alone in her castle in central <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The masterpiece, which she was said to keep under her bed, was a family heirloom, Ms. <PERSON> Poujade </PERSON> said. Rules of the order, a non-profit group specializing in hospital work, require it to sell such valuable possessions and use the money for its charities. Officials of the organization said several foreigners offered to buy the painting but it preferred to give <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> an opportunity to add it to de la Tour paintings already in the Louvre, including the famous `` Tricheur'' -LRB- Cheater -RRB-. Proceeds from the sale will help build a hospital in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for the mentally and physically handicapped, the order said.
