nfirmed in January. Since the department actually needs no authorization and could proceed under its general authority to conduct scientific research, the bill would be important for the collider only as a statement of congressional intent and limit on later appropriations, which the department does have to have. Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, D-Ala., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations energy subcommittee, has told the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> delegation his panel will approve no more than $ 60 million <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are finalists to host the super collider, which comprises a 53 miles-around tunnel and associated experimental facilities for smashing beams of protons into each other at energies 20 times the maximum possible today. Current law forbids the states from offering cash contributions during the selection process. The Energy Department is insisting on donation of the land, and the states may undertake site improvements _ which may be substantial. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials figure the state's land purchase, tunneling, road and other work is worth $ 590 million, and several states have submitted sealed bids that are to be opened only if that state is chosen. Before the vote on <ORGANIZATION> Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s amendment, Rep. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> officials had claimed they would have to drop out of the competition if a minimum-funds requirement were imposed. Others were skeptical that a $ 500 million requirement would deter anyone. `` Whoever wins ... is winning a $ 50 billion economic development program,'' said th