 The report was accompanied by a personal pledge from <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> `` to press at every opportunity for progress in improving allied defense capabilities and in sharing equitably the roles, risks and burdens of the alliance.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies `` make a substantial contribution to the common defense _ considerably more than they are often given credit for.'' But, he said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` in some areas is doing more than most of its partners.'' `` What is very clear is that there are substantial variations in performance among individual allies,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. The report says that in 1986, the latest year for which complete figures are available, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> allocated 6.8 percent of its gross national product to defense. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, which ranked second among the allies, allocated 6.1 percent. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was third with 5.1 percent, followed by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> at 4.8 percent and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> at 3.9 percent. The remaining nations had shares of 3.2 percent or less. Legislators in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have repeatedly criticized <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nations for not doing more. But they have rejected several attempts in the past three years to order <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> force reductions in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where 326,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops are stationed, and in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where there are about 63,000 American service personnel. `` Let's get smart and begin to tell our allies that we expect them to pay their fair share,'' said <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>. `` We are subsidizing their defense.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was even more blunt. `` The real purpose of this amendment is to demonstrate to our allies that we've had it. These people are stealing our jobs because we have been suckered into paying for their defense.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, D-Wash., called <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s plan `` a dangerous and irresponsible effort to bring troops home to deal with the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- trade problem. Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, opposed both plans, saying, `` this would be entirely counter-productive ... it is simply not possible to maintain the viability of a voluntary alliance of free countries if one of those countries tries to impose standards on the others.'' Rep. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bereuter </PERSON>, R-Neb., said, `` this would send the wrong message'' at a time when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is trying to urge <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries to spend more for non-nuclear weapons in the wake of the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear weapons But Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, D-Wis., said, `` it's time Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> quit being taken for uncle sucker. The bill authorizes <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending of $ 299.5 billion in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, which is the same amount proposed by the separate bill that will be considered next month by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Differences between the bills that pass each chamber will eventually be reconciled by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee.
