<HEAD>Bill Requires Drug-Free Workplaces for Energy Department
Contractors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee voted Friday to permit the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to withhold payments to some of its contractors until they demonstrate they are trying to maintain drug-free workplaces. The measure was attached as an amendment to the $ 3.1 billion <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> research authorization bill being considered by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Approval came on a 20-7 show of hands. Opponents said the amendment likely would prove to be counterproductive and inappropriate. Rep. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., a former prosecutor, said if he were a contractor, he would defend arrested employees in court to avoid interruption of his income from the department Supporters said it was time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to get serious about the nation's drug problem. `` Have any hearings been held?'' said Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` We have had hearings,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. `` Hearings are going on right now in the juvenile courts, in the jails and in the cemeteries.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s provision would require all contracts authorized under the bill to contain a provision permitting the contracting agency _ most often the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> _ to withhold payments `` upon proof of use, possession or possession with the intent to distribute of any controlled substance in violation of any federal, state or local law, by an employee in the workplace, as evidenced by the conviction of such employee in a court of competent jurisdiction'' until the contractor `` demonstrates to the agency that it has taken sufficient action to restore a drug-free workplace.'' Convictions arising out of an employer's good-faith efforts to enforce a drug-free workplace `` shall be considered substantial evidence that the employer is taking sufficient action,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s amendment said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said he was unable to reach any officials in a position to comment. The Energy Department provides funds to universities and others that operate laboratories which undertake a wide variety of research, ranging from the most secret nuclear weapons to environmental projects. Prospects for the drug provisions were not immediately clear, since the science authorization bill for the department has failed to get through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the past severl years. The department has permanent, general authority to conduct scientific research, and does so with money provided by appropriations committees.
