<HEAD>Over 500 Vehicles Seized In Latest Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it has seized over 500 vehicles, ranging from 18-wheelers to boats, from people caught carrying drugs into the country in the last five weeks. The new confiscation policy is part of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's `` Zero Tolerance'' anti-drug strategy announced last month. People caught bringing drugs into the country are arrested, their passport seized as evidence and the vehicle used to transport the drugs or drug paraphernalia is seized. In one instance, agents seized a $ 120,000 18-wheel tractor-trailer because the driver was carrying a single marijuana joint. `` If he's the owner of the truck, it's gone, he probably wo n't get it back,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, the No 2 <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> official, in an interview. In most cases, the government will have the vehicles sold at auction and the proceeds will go into the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. If the driver caught carring drugs is n't the owner, the vehicle will be turned over to the owner for a price that includes paying the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s costs involved in confiscating the vehicle. `` There's no question that Zero Tolerance is working,'' Customs commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The message is simple. We can not tolerate any drugs in our society, and if you get caught, you will be punished.'' A total of 542 cars, trucks, tractor-trailers and boats had been seized as of Tuesday under the new program. Four boats were seized in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and four in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` We hope the reaction is that they're shocked into reality,'' <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. `` Their cars are being taken away, they're being fingerprinted, photographed, taken before a magistrate and charged with an offense. We've had a lot of positive reaction from local communities.'' Federal criminal law allows the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to seize and dispose of vehicles involved in transporting drugs into the country. Some legal experts have criticized the portion of the policy that calls for seizing passports. They question the constitutionality of restricting a person's freedom to travel before the person has been convicted of a crime.
