f a `` national dialogue'' with opposition forces. Opposition leaders were not immediately available for comment. Panamanian Ambassador <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, a leader of the anti-Noriega forces in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of going beyond its authority in trying to negotiate <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political future. In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, anti-Noriega exiles called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal a surrender with cosmetics. `` This cosmetic solution will only take the country down the road to disaster,'' said <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallol </PERSON>, exiled representative of the Panamanian opposition umbrella group, the Civic Crusade. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Friday that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration reached a tentative agreement with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> under which he will step down as chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and de facto leader of the government but remain in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> this week. But he said the agreement was `` less than ideal'' because it did not include the general's departure from the country. The march Friday was called by the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which includes some labor groups that support the government and some parties in the governing coalition. One of the speakers at the rally, <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` The problem of <PERSON> N