<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra     04-29 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Defense Says Fair Trial Impossible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The legal requirements for using an unprecedented volume of government secrets in court will deprive Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and three Iran-Contra co-defendants of a fair trial, the defense said Friday. Classified Information Procedures Act -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> CIPA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- requirements that the defense serve notice of any plans to disclose classified information in court will give the prosecution an unfair advantage, the defense said in a motion filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The requirement `` imposes burdens on the defense unprecedented in American criminal law,'' lawyers for the fired <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide and his three co-defendants said in a joint motion. `` In the circumstances of this singular case involving an unprecedented volume of classified documents'' the requirement is `` clearly unconstitutional,'' the defense said. North, former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, busisinessmen <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> are accused of conspiring to defraud the governent by diverting U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. Under the law, the defense would be barred from using classified evidence in the trial unless it notifies the prosecution before the trial of all government secrets it plans to disclose. The requirement `` forces the defendants to furnish the prosecution virtually every detail of the defense case, including the defendants' anticipated testimony at trial, the testimony of other defense witnesses'' and the contents of all classified documents the lawyers intend to introduce as evidence or use to cross-examine prosecution witnesses, the defense said. `` This sweeping notice requirement ... violates the defendants' fundamental constitutional rights, including such basic guarantees as the privilege against compelled self-incrimination, the right to effective assistance of counsel, the right to cross-examine adverse witnesses and the right to due process of law,'' the defense said The requirement also deprives the defendants of the right to decide during the trial whether they want to testify in their own defense. `` If the defendants do not include the substance of their anticipated testimony in their notice, then they run a grave risk that the court will preclude large portions of their testimony,'' the defense said. `` On the other hand, the defense lacks the information necessary to make an informed decision that the defendants will testify, since the defense does not know how the prosecution's case will fare at any trial,'' the brief said. The problem is particularly acute because the indictment, as described by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, `` alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.'' The difficulty is compounded by the large volume of documents. Independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> has said as many as 50,000 pages of classified documents collected during his investigation are relevant to the case. And <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has ruled that the defense should have an opportunity to examine relevant portions of another 250,000 pages. `` The defense can reasonably predict that hundreds of thousands of pages of classified material not yet inventoried, and volumes of classified testimony, will ultimately be involved in the case,'' said the joint motion by lawyers for the four defendants. The defense motion illustrated the difficulty of applying the disclosure rule to cross-examination. `` Armed with the defendant's notice,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> can tailor his case `` to blunt the force of the defense cross-examination. The notice may alert the prosecution to specific areas of vulnerability of which it had been not aware.''
</TEXT>
