<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of workers struck for higher pay at a heavy machinery plant Friday, capping a week of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor trouble since communist authorities suppressed the Solidarity union more than six years ago. <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> police detained <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, a senior adviser to the outlawed Solidarity federation. A member of <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>'s household said three plainclothesmen arrived at his home in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> was being interviewed by telephone by a Western radio station. Strikes began Monday with bus and streetcar drivers leaving their jobs in the western city of <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION>. Workers at the huge <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> steel works at <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> in the southern industrial belt, struck Tuesday and on Friday came the strike at the machinery plant at <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, 65 miles east of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. Solidarity activists in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s municipal transport company said in a statement they were calling a strike for 6 a.m. Saturday to support the <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> action. Workers demand pay increases of 50 percent or more. Prices rose 42 percent in the first three months of 1988 because the government reduced subsidies on many consumer items. Sunday is May Day, the international Labor Day traditionally celebrated by the government and used by Polish workers to air their grievances publicly. Streets were festooned in advance with red <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> banners, red-and-white Polish flags and posters saying `` Workers of All Lands Unite.'' The government has both threatened dismissals and promised to improve wages. At <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION>, the 2,800 drivers won a 60 percent pay increase ater an 11-hour strike. Officials of Solidarity threatened more strikes if authorities use force against strikers. They said workers in at least four other cities had declared support for the Nowa Huta action and issued strike alerts. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, Solidarity's founder, said in a statement: `` I appeal to authorities to maintain reason. I am warning against the return to the policy of terror, which is apparently supposed to defend reforms, while in reality it defends the way of governing which has led <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to ruin.'' He said statements by government officials indicated they might use force and urged <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s workers `` to show solidarity'' with the strikers `` in case violence takes place.'' An aide read the statement by telephone from <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s apartment in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where the 1983 Nobel Peace laureate works as a shipyard electrician. The aide, who asked that his name not be used, said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> instructed regional Solidarity leaders to organize protests and strikes if the government uses force. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said an attempt to start a strike failed at the 18,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Stalowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wola </ORGANIZATION> heavy machinery plant, but the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said later at least one department was shut down. A Roman Catholic priest in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, the Rev. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemiec </PERSON>, said about 7,000 strikers were occupying three department and the strike began when about 5,000 first-shift employees quit working. He said management tried to lock out most of the second-shift workers but some broke in. <PERSON> Niemiec </PERSON> said the number of strikers could be as high as 9,000, but he could not confirm the figure. He said the information came from a member of the strike committee. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, strikers customarily go to their places of employment but do not work. Often they hold meetings or pass out leaflets. About 12,000 workers were striking for a fourth day at the Lenin plant in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, which means <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mill </ORGANIZATION> and was built as a model city in the 1950s just outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. Management representatives met with the plant's government-sanctioned union but refused to deal with the unofficial committee that claims to represent at least half the plant's 32,000 workers The <ORGANIZATION> Nowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huta </ORGANIZATION> strike is the biggfest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since those that swept the country after food price increases in 1980, bringing down a government and giving birth to Solidarity. The independent union federation was suppressed, then outlawed, after martial law was declared in December 1981. Urban said there had been `` preventative detentions'' in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> this week, but did not say how many. <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, the Solidarity adviser, said by telephone before his detention that 25 people had been picked up around the country in the past two days. <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, an adviser to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, said police stopped his car Thursday in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> and detained him, Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bujak </PERSON> remained in custody. <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERS