<HEAD>Chemical Plant Partially Closed As Public Health Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities on Friday shut down some production facilities at a chemical plant in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> after environmentalists contended the equipment increased cases of cancer and other diseases. Soviet television said two units producing chloroprene rubber were taken out of production Friday morning at the <ORGANIZATION> Nairit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> because they caused `` irreparable harm to the city's ecology and people's health.'' The decision was made due to `` multiple demands of residents of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> about a complicated ecological situation,'' an announcer said. A correspondent for the television news program Vremya reported from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> that the two units sent 3,500 tons of pollutants into the air annually. The report showed workers turning off valves on the units, built in the late 1930s. The plant will continue to produce other items, including anti-corrosive paint, according to the report. The shutdown was an example of how Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or openness, has made authorities more responsive to citizens' complaints. The Soviet news media has carried a number of reports about industrial pollution as a threat to public health. Many cities are reported to be in violation of national air pollution standards. In January, the government formed a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>. At least 3,000 Armenians marched in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> Oct. 17 to demand the shutdown of <LOCATION> Nairit </LOCATION> and a nuclear power station. Soviet television said the national Cabinet, known as the