y involved as a prosecutor. Federal agents arrested a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> man after finding more than 4 pounds of cocaine in his house, and the man retained two <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> lawyers, one of whom later became a target in `` Operation Greylord,'' an investigation of corruption in <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, Ill. The target, <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Glass </PERSON>, contacted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and offered to provide drug-related information in exchange for favorable treatment of his case. His offer was accepted and he met periodically with <PERSON> Turow </PERSON>. When Glass informed <PERSON> Turow </PERSON> he was representing the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> man, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ofshe </PERSON>, in the drug case, <PERSON> Turow </PERSON> encouraged him to proceed as an informant and <PERSON> Turow </PERSON> obtained permission to place a microphone on Glass to secretly record conversations between him and <PERSON> Ofshe </PERSON>, according to the federal appeals court. <PERSON> Turow </PERSON> warned him not to reveal any privileged attorney-client conversations. When <PERSON> Ofshe </PERSON> and his other lawyer discovered that Glass had been acting as an informant, they tried unsuccessfully to have the case dismissed. The appeals court rejected the request for dismissal last June, but said that `` we do not condone the government's use of criminal defense attorneys as informants against their clients.'' Last November, a three-judge panel of the appeals court rejected <PERSON> Turow </PERSON>'s request to delete from the record its previous rebuke, saying it was troubled by `` the ethical ramifications'' of his conduct and that `` we believe that <PERSON> Turow </PERSON> may have committed an obstruction of justice.
