<HEAD>Scientists From More Than 17 Countries Plan International Space
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists from around the globe gathered Friday to plan for International Space Year in 1992 and were called the spiritual descendants of <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON>. `` You are explorers who know of enduring hardship ... to triumph over great natural obstacles,'' said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyerson </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-ISY </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which is supervising the planning. The organization is orchestrating a series of space projects to commemorate the 500th anniversary of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>' first voyage to the New World in 1492. `` This effort unites the universal themes ... that have powered the human spirit in the past and continue to point to a future of unlimited horizons,'' added <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, the chief of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Nearly 90 scientists from 17 space agencies, including those of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and Western European, opened the three-day meeting at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>. The scientists are planning projects that will use space satellites to research global problems including acid rain, ozone depletion and the apparent gradual warming of the Earth's climate, known as the greenhouse effect. Images of the planet from space, <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said, have `` triggered an awareness of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> as a fragile and most precious life support system, one made even more precious because ... it is the only body in our solar system to harbor and nourish life.'' The space year will include TV specials, expositions and trade fairs. The events will help persuade people and governments that space technology is worth its high cost, said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of several western European nations. `` It's easy to convince the public and political masters of the glamor projects like space travel ... but harder to maintain the enthusiasm and funding levels for the long period needed to observe Earth,'' <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> said.
