<HEAD>Survey: 4 Out Of 10 American Professionals Say Japan's Economy
Threatens U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four out of every 10 American professionals surveyed believe <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economic power is a threat to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and only 1 percent said U.S.-Japanese relations are very good, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The survey involved 1,550 politicians, lawyers and other professionals and indicated most believe <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has failed to fulfill its international responsibilities commensurate with its stature as an economic power, said the report released Thursday. The survey, widely carried in Japanese newspapers Friday, was conducted by the U.S.-based Gallup Organization for the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The professionals were selected randomly from `` Who's Who in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Asked if they considered <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s growing economic power to be a benefit or threat to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 40 percent of the respondents said it was a threat, up from 37 percent in 1987 and the highest level since the Foreign Ministry began the annual poll of prominent Americans in 1972. About 47 percent said they thought <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s growing economic strength benefited the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, down from 52 percent last year and a record low, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. About 70 percent of respondents said they felt Japanese high technology presented a serious challenge to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Only about 1 percent said they felt relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were `` very good,'' while about 35 percent rated them as `` good,'' 52 percent said they were `` normal'' and 11 percent called them `` not good.'' The survey showed 61 percent of those questioned believe <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has done `` nothing at all'' to assume its share of world responsibilities, despite its strong economic performance. Twenty-eight percent said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has assumed its due duties `` to some extent.'' Only eight percent of the respondents said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has `` fully'' played up to its role as the second largest economic power in the Western world after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to the report. It said those who considered <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> an important country for `` the development and stability of the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> region'' totaled 43 percent, up from 41 percent in the 1987 survey. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> took second place with 35 percent of those surveyed in the poll. Regarding agricultural trade, 25 percent said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should immediately open up its markets to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm products, up eight points from 1987. Fifty-eight percent said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> should disband its farm market barriers on a gradual basis.
