<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rebels on Friday removed a major obstacle to agreement in their talks with the government to work out details of a cease-fire pact signed last month. The top rebel leader announced that the insurgents, known as Contras, will not insist that their fighters be resupplied with weapons and ammunition when they gather in seven cease-fire zones during a permanent truce that is being considered. `` We have desisted from receiving replacements of weapons and ammunition in the zones and we accept the concept of sovereignty and indivisibility of national territory,'' <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> told a news conference. Previously the Contras insisted that the cease-fire zones be autonomous. But <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> also said the Contras rejected the Sandinista government's demand that all humanitarian aid to the rebels be channeled through the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. The rebels expect $ 17.7 million in humanitarian aid already approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> told reporters earlier Friday that the rebels have suffered deep internal divisions and some segments have rejected disarming and returning to civilian life. The rebels on Friday rejected a government proposal to extend by 30 days a 60-day cease-fire that began April 1. They said the extension showed `` a lack of good will to fulfill the agreements.'' The cease-fire agreement was signed on March 23. Sandinista officials said the rebel refusal to agree to an extension showed the Contras were more interested in a truce than a permanent peace. The interim cease-fire accord calls for the Contras to move into cease-fire zones while talks continue on a long-term accord. Contra leaders insist the sides agree upon just how much freedom the rebels will have within those zones. As the two sides continued their talks in the Nicaraguan capital, police used rubber truncheons to break up a demonstration at the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella group for anti-Sandinista unions, and detained seven people. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Huembes </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinate </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of unions and parties opposed to the government, said four workers were arrested outside the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. He said they were en route to the demonstration in front of the confederation building. Both the construction workers and the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> belong to the coordinate. The arrests came five days after 38 construction workers and auto mechanics began a hunger strike for higher salaries. Police cordoned off the entrance of the union headquarters where about 150 people, including the hunger strikers, huddled behind the metal grates of the building. A banner strung across the building said: `` We prefer to die of hunger fighting with dignity than to die working as slaves.'' About 1,500 workers from both industries have staged wildcat strikes since Feb. 25 demanding higher wages. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Osejo </PERSON>, head of privately-owned <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, which broadcast the news of the police actions, said Interior Minister <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> punched him in the mouth when he was summoned to the minister's office on Friday. He said <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> apologized later. <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> is also a leader of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, a private watchdog group. The weapons issue has been a major one in the Contra-Sandinista talks, particularly whether the rebels can keep their arms. The rebels say they will disarm when <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is on the `` irreversible road to democracy.'' The Sandinistas say disarming is fundamental to the pact. But <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said an apparent split among Contra leaders made such negotiations more difficult. The rebels deny the split. The rebels had been supplied arms and weapons since 1981 through CIA-operated air drops that stopped earlier this year when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rejected President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request for renewed military aid. Government newspapers on Friday quoted President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> as saying that $ 17.9 million in U.S.-approved aid for children orphaned or injured in the war would be permitted only if channeled through neutral organizations. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> was quoted as saying his side understood the `` good intentions'' involved in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' approving the money, `` but we can not allow it to arrive through political organisms that are clearly against the revolution.'' The aid, part of a nearly $ 48 million Contra aid package, was to be funneled to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> through the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>.
