<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> proposed Friday making employers put warning tags or locks on machinery as it is being cleaned or serviced _ nine years after unions requested the regulation and more than 1,000 deaths later as a result of its absence. The proposed regulations, which the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> estimates will save 122 lives and prevent 60,000 injuries annually, had languished at the White House for nearly a year. Their publication in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION> on Friday occurred just one week after <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., cited them in congressional hearings as an example of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's `` decision to let workers die while waiting on a standard. Employers under the proposal would have to adopt uniform procedures to `` lock out'' or `` tag out'' switches, valves or other controls to prevent the start up of machines while they are being cleaned or serviced. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials estimated about 7 percent of all occupational fatalities and 2 per cent of accident-caused injuries in the workplace occur now because such equipment is inadvertently restarted while someone is working on it. `` This rule would mean safer working conditions for millions of employees in general industry,'' Assistant Labor Secretary and <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> said Friday. `` Very simple lockout, tagout measures, which take only a few minutes, can prevent up to 10 percent of all the serious injuries in some major manufacturing industries,'' <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> said. The agency said the regulations will apply to some 1.6 million employers and cover an estimated 39 million workers at an estimated total annual cost of $ 135 million to businesses. They are aimed chiefly at machine operators and laborers who work around packaging and wrapping equipment, conveyors and printing presses, which are associated with the highest proportion of the accidents, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials said. As an example, the agency cited one worker who had leaned his head into a flour batch mixer and whose neck was crushed when another worker inadvertently turned the machine on. The so-called `` performance-oriented'' regulations would require employers only to follow certain steps in turning off equipment and `` minimize'' the potential for inadvertently reactivating it. Unions that began petitioning the agency for the regulations in 1979 had wanted it to mandate as law specific procedures developed by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. However, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said it would include the <ORGANIZATION> ANSI </ORGANIZATION> standards only as `` detailed voluntary guidelines'' in an appendix to the regulations. The agency noted that business groups had wanted the <ORGANIZATION> ANSI </ORGANIZATION> standards eliminated entirely from the appendix out of fears that a court might later interpret them as mandatory. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Molovich </PERSON>, a safety specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, predicted employers will ignore the voluntary guidelines and `` take the cheapest way out'' by using cardboard warning tags instead of locks to prevent a machine from being turned on. `` There will be no positive means of assuring that the equipment wo n't start,'' <PERSON> Molovich </PERSON> said of the proposed regulations. `` They would be better off cutting it into four-inch squares and putting it in the outhouse.'' The proposal also exempts millions of companies and workers in agriculture, oil and gas drilling, electric utilities, the maritime industry and construction. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials said protections for them will be included in other regulations to be proposed later. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> official who worked on the regulations for more than a decade, testified at the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearings last week that the agency had first seen a need for them back in 1977. But <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> took no serious action until 1979, when the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, reacting to the deaths of 22 of its members in related accidents the previous five years, formally asked the government for emergency action. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> denied that request and similar pleas in 1982 and 1986 from other unions. And <PERSON> Scully </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel that officials in the agency were taken off any work on them at all in 1981 and 1982. However, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> promised in 1983 to issue in 1984 what was published Friday. Copies of the agency's regulatory agenda showed similar promises in 1984, 1985 and 1986. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials said Friday that the proposed regulation was sent to the White House Office of Management and Budget in May 1987 for approval but was not acted on there until last month. The agency estimates it will be a minimum of another year before the regulations are actually enacted.
</TEXT>
