<HEAD>Fauci Praises Scientists, But Says Staff Shortages Have Delayed
Drug Trials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the federal agency researching AIDS drugs said Friday he is basically satisfied with the job scientists are doing, but acknowledged that some human trials have been delayed due to lack of money. Dr. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on human resources that about 3,500 AIDS patients are involved in some 30 clinical trials financed with <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> grants. `` We're never satisfied, but we think we've done a pretty good job under the circumstances,'' <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said under questioning from Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, the panel chairman, and other committee members. Pressed by <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> estimated that some trials of AIDS drugs that could have been started this year were delayed for a year, pending the new budget cycle, due to staff shortages. <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said that lack of personnel was `` almost exclusively'' the reason why still more experimental drugs have not yet entered clinical trials. He said his institute _ one arm of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> _ had requested 127 additional staff members for the current fiscal year, but had received only 11 new slots in the budget approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` The dimension of the shortfall is such that you ca n't possibly meet your needs,'' concluded <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. A bill passed overwhelmingly by the