<HEAD>Forgery Murders Inspire Rash of Books and TV Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One not-yet-published book about the <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> forgery murders has been sold to television and another to film, but that does n't bother authors <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. They believe their own volume, `` Salamander: The Story of the Mormon Forgery Murders,'' is the one that will be read by the Mormon community which <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> betrayed. `` The Mormon Murders: A True Story of Greed, Forgery, Deceit and Death,'' by <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Naifeh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and published by <PERSON> Weidenfeld </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nicolson </PERSON>, is scheduled for August release. It has been sold to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> as a possible miniseries. `` A Gathering of Saints: A True Story of Money, Murder and Deceit,'' by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON>, has a September publishing date. Film rights were purchased by 20th Century <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, a writer and architect, was a friend of <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>'s first victim, a fellow history buff. <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON> was a newspaper reporter who used <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> as a source early in the <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> story. Their collaboration began as an effort to explain <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> to the Mormons. Two years and 556 pages later, Signature Books of <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, is seeking to beat two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> publishers out of a share of the national market. `` I think both of us were motivated by a need to know and to communicate with our own subculture,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said, but they decided later to write for non-Mormon readers as well. For six years that unstructured Mormon subculture of about 3,000 scholars, writers, artists and historians had been dazzled and intrigued by <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>'s finds of supposedly historical documents that forced a sometimes painful re-examination of Mormon origins. The enigmatic <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>'s success gave him ready access to the high church officials numbered among his most avid customers. He had begun to forge lucrative American historical and literary documents when, under pressure to produce promised documents that did n't exist, he turned to murder to cover his tracks. His first bomb on Oct. 15, 1985, killed a young Mormon bishop, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON>, who had bought and donated <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>'s most famous creation, the so-called `` Salamander Letter,'' to the church. The `` Salamander Letter'' was purported to have been written by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, an early associate of church founder <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. It gives an account of <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s finding of gold plates _ from which he said he translated the `` Book of Mormon'' _ which is contrary to the official church version. The letter said an `` old spirit'' directed <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> to the plates, then transformed itself into a white salamander. The official church version has it that an angel named <LOCATION> Moroni </LOCATION> directed <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> to the plates in 1827. A second bomb, intended to divert suspicion from <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>, killed <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, wife of a former <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON> business partner. But a third bomb the next day _ which <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> called a suicide device _ seriously injured its maker and exposed him as the likely killer. Fifteen months later, in a controversial pre-trial plea bargain, <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> admitted his guilt, detailed his forgeries and was sentenced to five years to life in prison. `` <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> was such an equal opportunity rip-off artist ... because he took everybody for what they were worth,'' said <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON>, who quit her job at the <ORGANIZATION> Deseret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in order to work on the book. `` It's not just that he exploited the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- secrecy or the paranoia that people criticize, but he also exploited the faith, and the values and the trust and the belief. Whatever people had to give, he exploited,'' she said. But `` Salamander'' is not merely an indictment of a master manipulator and forger. The authors sought in their interviews with some 200 sources to explain who and what had shaped a man for whom deceit was the means and the end. `` I think he had a double difficulty,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. `` His parentage was first-generation German and very authoritarian. And then you add to that the fact they were orthodox, conservative Mormons, which carres another layer of authoritarianism.'' An inquisitive boy, <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> could n't raise questions in that environment, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. Thus, he was a secret agnostic while serving a mission for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jesus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> of Latter-day Saints and, more than a decade later, fooled a lie detector about the bombings. `` He comes right out of the heart of the culture in every way,'' <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON> said. `` And that's what was so fascinating to me about the story is that everything fed into it _ the history, the theology, the polygamy, everything. And you've got it right there on the doorstep of the Church Office Building.'' The authors sought to interview <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON>, 33, at <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION>, where the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION> recently told him he will spend the rest of his life. But the inmate refused. <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> were somewhat more successful with three church leaders who figured in the <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> story. They provided written answers to a dozen typed questions. Their reticence was understandable; <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> had cast them, as he had friends and family, in the role of dupe. `` I think there was a strong instinct to protect the institution,'' said <PERSON> Sillitoe </PERSON>, who regrets that the <PERSON> Hofmann </PERSON> case seems to have invigorated the faith's `` traditional, anti-intellectual segment.'' For Signature Books, `` Salamander'' is unique. The company, founded in 1981 to publish Mormon-related works, produced just six titles in 1987 and never has spent more than $ 15,000 to promote any one book. The Roberts-Sillitoe work has up to $ 100,000 in advertising. A publicist has been hired, the authors are touring and there is a first printing of 15,000 copies, more than double Signature's previous high
