<HEAD>Breaching the Acting Barrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Travanti </PERSON>, no longer the tight-lipped <PERSON> Furillo </PERSON> of `` Hill Street Blues,'' is entering a new phase in his campaign to breach `` that mythical, mystical, invisible barrier'' that separates television from movie actors. <PERSON> Travanti </PERSON> can be seen in theaters this month in `` Midnight Crossing,'' a mystery thriller from <ORGANIZATION> Vestron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. He plays the husband of <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON>, who is blinded with glaucoma, and both embark on a <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> yacht cruise that becomes enmeshed in stolen treasure and murder. <PERSON> Travanti </PERSON> discussed his life after `` Hill Street Blues'' at his <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palisades </LOCATION> home where his neighbors are <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Forsythe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzenegger </PERSON>. The series has obviously provided <PERSON> Travanti </PERSON> with prosperity. But it also left him with a new challenge. `` The problem for many actors,'' he said, `` is that mystical, mythical barrier that you have to cross through a misty field. You're on this side of it and you're called ` a television actor.' Or you're called ` a theater actor.' On the other side is the cinema _ motion pictures, feature films. `` Somehow they see you coming and they do n't want you to cross over. I do n't know why. Nobody has been able to explain it. They used to say: ` People do n't want to pay to see someone when they can see him free.' That's all changed. `` And so you face that strange phenomenon of crossing over that foggy field and coming out the other side and becoming a ` movie actor.' It has nothing to do with ability necessarily, or how you look or how you sound. Some make it, and some do n't. `` Since I finished the series last year, I've done what I wished I could do. I went from ` Midnight Crossing' to a play, ` I Never Sang for My Father,' which had a successful six-month tour. And now I'm doing another movie with <PERSON> Kris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristofferson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Ladd </PERSON>, ` Millennium.' So by summer I will have done two feature films and a successful play tour. And my next television appearance will be an American Playhouse version of the play in June.'' The actor does n't worry about escaping the persona of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Furillo </PERSON>. `` I did that in the first season of ` Hill Street Blues,''' he said, `` by playing totally different characters in television movies, ` Adam' and ` A Case of Libel.' And I also played <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON> on television. `` Not all of the characters have been straight-arrow like the captain. The guy I played in ` A Matter of Libel' was ... complex. ... The guy in ` Midnight Crossing' is maybe a less-controlled cousin of that fellow, so to speak. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON>, one of the heroes of our time, was also a complicated man, though we could n't show much of that in a two-hour movie.'' <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Travanti </PERSON> is a late bloomer as an actor. `` I charged through college -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- in three years with <LOCATION> Phi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kappa </LOCATION> and every other honor. I knocked my brains out. I do n't know what ... I was rushing toward. No matter how fast I ran, it turned out I could n't get there any faster than I was supposed to. `` In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it all screeched to a crawl,'' he said. `` Many actors, who are told they are talented in school or regional theaters, get to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and get stonewalled _ not frozen out; I worked all the time. I was just so confused and so neurotic that I drove myself crazy. And I drove others around me crazy. `` For a long time I limped along and bumped along and hiccupped along. I always made a living _ this fall will mark 25 years as an actor, never having to work as anything else. The big turning point came 15 years ago when I found sobriety,'' he said, referring to his alcoholism. `` I do n't want to belabor that, because I do n't want it to be an overpowering identity of mine. But I am willing to mention it and talk about it privately. `` Since then it's been a matter of patiently trudging, chugging, moving steadily along and hoping for a break.''
