<HEAD>The Pulitzer Collection of Modern Art on Exhibit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN J. MULLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was an undergraduate at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1935, he bought a striking painting by <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON>, beginning an extraordinary collection of modern art. The collection grew to more than 250 paintings, drawings and sculptures in the ensuing half-century. Pulitzer recently returned to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> for the opening of an exhibit featuring 86 of his those works. More than 40 artists are represented in the exhibit, which will be at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> until June 12 when it moves to the <ORGANIZATION> Saint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> from July 8 through Aug. 28. `` There are perhaps only three or four museums in the country who could put together, from their own collections, a display to match the depth and breadth of this one,'' said <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowron </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museums </ORGANIZATION>. Included are 12 works by <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, four each by <PERSON> Monet </PERSON>, <PERSON> Klee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miro </PERSON>; three each by <PERSON> Degas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Matisse </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lipchitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON>; and pieces by <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brancusi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>. `` I wanted to buy creative art that would have a validity and vitality that would transcend fashion,'' said <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON>, whose grandfather's will established the Pulitzer Prizes in journalism and the arts. `` I was much more interested in the living rather than going deeply into the past,'' he said, explaining why he chose to collect modern art. A fine arts major at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> graduated in 1936 and joined the staff of the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Post-Dispatch </LOCATION>. He became its editor and publisher and now is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Pulitzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He has been generous with his purchases, giving pieces to museums, including the <PERSON> Fogg </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Saint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, which has that first <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON>, `` Elvira Resting at a Table.'' Some remain at his home. `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> started -LRB- collecting -RRB- from the purest of reasons _ love of art,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, chief curator of the <ORGANIZATION> Saint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>. `` And, he's not cashing in his chips,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> added, referring to collectors who sell for profit. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bowron </PERSON> and <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss-Levy </PERSON>, curator of prints, drawings and photographs at the <LOCATION> Saint </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, made the selections from the Pulitzer collection to put in the exhibit. `` It was intended to demonstrate the quality and range of the collection,'' <PERSON> Bowron </PERSON> said of their choices, and noted that <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> also had a say. `` We made the initial selection, but then <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>, with his unerring eye, said, ` You must put in this one and that one,''' <PERSON> Bowron </PERSON> said. Installing the exhibit was difficult because the works were so varied in size, media and style. One perspective on the exhibit, said <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, is that <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> bought the <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON> four years before <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Serra </PERSON>, who has a painting, a drawing and a sculpture in the show, was born. `` The collection is very much a synopsis of mainstream modernism and its evolving,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. `` In a certain sense we distilled them -LRB- the selections -RRB- out of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>'s distillation, a summary history of modern art in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It is a history of modern art.'' The exhibit also marks the publication by the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museums </ORGANIZATION> of the fourth volume of the catalog of the Pulitzer collection. It was written by <PERSON> Angelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Zander </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudenstine </PERSON>, a curator and scholar and, as a member of the visiting committee, an adviser to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s fine arts department. `` I have said ... to <PERSON> Angelica </PERSON>, if she ever departs from, her profession as art historian, I would like to hire her for the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Post-Dispatch </LOCATION> as an investigative reporter,'' <PERSON> Pulitzer </PERSON> said.
