<HEAD>Earnings Hot, Stock Market Not</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If current corporate earnings were the only determinant of trends in stock prices, the market would surely be thriving right now. Companies in a wide variety of industries, big names and small, have lately posted strong profit gains for the first quarter. And most analysts agree that the earning outlook remains bright for the balance of the year. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> calculates that the several hundred companies included in its industrial index chalked up a 39 percent increase in profits last year. For 1988, it estimates a further 21 percent gain. The earnings picture has been much stronger than would be suggested by the pace of overall economic growth in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has been moderate at most. As <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> at the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> observed: `` Recent cost-cutting and streamlining have produced earnings increases that have oustripped the economy's sluggish pace. A weak dollar has helped industrial <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> gain a better competitive position in world markets. Prominent companies like <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, to cite two examples from the past few days, have accompanied their latest reports with announcements of dividend increases. But while the earnings trend may be causing great cheer in executive suites around the country, it has met with a chilly reception on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, where stock prices continue to drift around aimlessly on low volume. `` The market has n't yet rewarded positive surprises, but has punished disappointments,'' said <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. This is hardly the first time, of course, that the stock market has been seemingly out of synch with the producing and consuming economy. The question investors have to grapple with is not how earnings are doing now, but what they will look like six months, a year or more in the future. Just how far ahead the market, in its collective vision, can `` see'' is a matter of long-standing debate. It can be argued that many of the gains now being posted in corporate profits were `` discounted,'' or foreshadowed in stock prices, during the great bull market of 1982-87. In early 1987, notes <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's in its advisory publication The Outlook, the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P industrial stocks traded at prices as much as 23 times their current earnings. Recently, the P-E ratio has been running at a much more conservative 12 to 1, depressed by the crash last fall and more recent worries about rising interest rates and inflation. Even if P-Es merely hold at their recent levels, a continued rise in earnings would theoretically translate into high stock prices. `` A 20 percent increase in 1988 earnings -LRB- of companies in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average -RRB- would be enough to support a Dow industrial average of 2,800,'' argues <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON> in his advisory letter <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON>'s Journal. `` And there is at least the possibility that earnings gains this year will exceed 20 percent.'' More pessimistic observers contend earnings do n't carry much weight in times of high or rising interest rates. `` Even as the threat of recession recedes and strong corporate earnings are reported,'' say analysts at <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, they believe `` stock-price earnings multiples will be trending lower over the course of 1988.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday editions, May 2</NOTE>
