<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Malden Adv13-15   04-29 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Malden, Adv 13-15,0787</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv13-15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 13-15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Malden </PERSON> says `` My Father, My Son'' is the story of a close-knit family rather than a story of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the tragedy of Agent Orange. <PERSON> Malden </PERSON> plays Adm. <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who ordered the use of the chemical defoliant Agent Orange to cler the jungle away from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s rivers to protect <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> patrol boats. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Carradine </PERSON> plays his son, <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a former patrol boat skipper, who believes his cancer was caused by the defoliant. `` I think what you're going to see is a terrific family love story,'' said <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>. `` I've never seen a family so tight.'' The two-hour film is based on the book the Zumwalts wrote about their experiences. The movie, which <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> will televise Sunday, May 22, was shot in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. `` It's a fascinating story,'' said <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>. `` When the admiral was assigned to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, his son wanted to go, too. And when the admiral gets there he realizes the <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> are knocking off the boat crews left and right because the jungle goes right down to the river. It was giving them protection. `` The admiral heard they were using Agent Orange in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> to kill weeds on some farms. He looked into it and then ordered its use. The irony is that his son was captain of one of those little river boats, and his son was the only one on his boat to get sick.'' <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> was afflicted with two kinds of cancer, lymphoma and <PERSON> Hodgkin </PERSON>'s Disease, which both Zumwalts believe was caused by Agent Orange. He has undergone chemotherapy, radiation and bone marrow transplants. `` The admiral did some investigating later and found the government had led him astray about Agent Orange,'' said <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>. `` The government knew there was a higher rate of cancer in those areas where it was used as a defoliant and withheld the information.'' In addition, the younger <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> has a son with a learning disability. `` Elmo and his wife came with their two children when we were shooting the boat scenes,'' said <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>. `` They built a little village in the swamp. The boy was so excited. I was in uniform and wearing the admiral's name badge. <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> told his son, who's about 10 or 12, ` This is grandpa.' `` All that day I was grandpa to the boy and he kept kissing me. On the boat going back he sat next to me. His affection was so touching. I had to look the other way. I think the admiral feels he's the cause of <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON>'s and the boy's problem. I think he feels guilty.'' This was not <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>'s first military role. He played Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> in `` Patton.'' He was in `` Winged Victory,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> stage show in World War II that was also filmed as a movie. `` After the war, I was in every kind of war movie,'' he said. `` I was a private, a corporal and I was the good sergeant to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Widmark </PERSON>'s tough sergeant in ` Take the High Ground.''' <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>, who had made his movie debut before the war, won an Oscar as best supporting actor for `` A Streetcar Named Desire.'' Three years later, he teamed up with <PERSON> Marlon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brando </PERSON> again for `` On the Waterfront.'' Most recently, he co-starred in the Barbra Streisand movie `` Nuts.'' <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>, well-known to television audiences for his 15 years as spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> travelers checks, played Lt. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> in the TV series `` Streets of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.'' His co-star, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, just won an Academy Award as best actor for `` Wall Street.'' <PERSON> Malden </PERSON>'s only other series was `` Skag,'' in which he played a steel mill worker. That was a role he played in real life in his hometown of <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, before he became an actor. `` My father was an amateur actor in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and after he came to this country he organized 30 church choirs,'' he said. `` He was president for six years of the Serbian Singing Society of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. He was a milkman and did that when he had time off. `` I decided to become an actor because I was n't getting anywhere in the mills. I had friends at the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and decided to go there. When I told my father he said, ` Are you crazy? You want to give up a good job in the middle of the Depression?' Thank God for my mother. She said to give it a try.''
