<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Foreign Business,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mineral Mining Limited To Brazilian Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a victory for <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s left, lawmakers re-writing <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s authoritarian constitution have voted overwhelmingly to limit mineral mining to domestic companies. The Thursday night vote came on the heels of a Wednesday vote to give special protections to certain domestically-owned enterprises, a move that foreign businessmen indicated may discourage the influx of foreign capital to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s beleaguered economy. Legislators doubling as a constituent assembly sang the national anthem Thursday night after voting to prohibit foreign companies from mining for minerals or drilling for hydraulic energy. The constitutional article would give foreign companies such as subsidiaries of British Petroleum, bauxite mining companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alcoa </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s Anglo-American Company a five-year grace period to adapt to the new legislation. Foreign-owned companies control 20 percent of mining rights or requests for mining rights in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Private domestic companies own 52 percent and state-run companies own 18 percent. Also on Thursday, legislators voted 303-156 to maintain present legislation allowing foreign participation in petroleum distribution. A radical proposal that was rejected would have barred <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Richfield </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> from selling gasoline in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Foreign companies now hold 55 percent of the market here. The Thursday votes followed Wednesday's equally radical decisions making it harder and less inviting for foreign companies to operate in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. In a bipartisan agreement, law-makers voted to define what constitutes a `` Brazilian company'' and a `` domestic-capital Brazilian company.'' The key distinction is that domestic-capital companies will enjoy as yet-undetermined `` protection and special benefits'' and will be allowed to develop the also yet-undetermined `` strategic or essential'' areas of the economy. Legislators decided that a domestic-capital company must have a majority of its voting capital and its decision-making power belonging permanently to residents of this country. A Brazilian company would be simply any company established under Brazilian law. The congress is expected to finish <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s eighth constitution late this year. Rep. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavalcanti </PERSON>, of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the new laws prevent multinationals from being considered national, that is Brazilian, concerns. `` It's not fair that, say, a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> has the right and the access to Brazilian savings,'' she said. `` This way, they can come in but with their own investments and own foreign savings.'' But the new statutes were widely considered nationalistic, and the initial reaction of foreign businessmen was negative. `` The red flag is up for foreign capital,'' said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Lund </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Sao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paulo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. `` It is unfortunate because they made it more difficult to do business in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Lund </PERSON>, a businessman who has lived in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> since 1962, said the law will be harmful to the Brazilian economy by limiting the vital influx of foreign capital. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is strapped with a huge foreign debt of $ 121 billion, inflation of over 16 percent monthly and one of the world's most unequal distributions of wealth. About two-thirds of the nation's 143 million people earn less than $ 40 a week `` Brazilians have the right to change their own laws, but if their true objective is to change the life of millions of Brazilians, you first have to have an economy that will generate wealth,'' said <PERSON> Lund </PERSON>. `` You ca n't do that by limiting foreign capital.'' <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Sauer </PERSON>, a West German-born naturalized Brazilian who is president of <ORGANIZATION> Autolatina </ORGANIZATION>, the local holding group for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>, said `` discrimination will not resolve the economic problems of this country.''
</TEXT>
