<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar turned in a mixed performance in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> early today as traders awaited release of economic data from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Gold prices dipped below $ 450 a troy ounce. The dollar drifted within a narrow range in the first hours of European trading. Late month commercial dealings kept the market moderately active, but many players were staying to the sidelines prior to the release later today of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> index of leading economic indicators for March. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the pound was quoted at 1.8765 dollars, up slightly from 1.8755 dollars late Thursday. Other dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at midmorning, compared with late Thursday, were: 1.6675 West German marks, down from 1.6705; 1.3865 Swiss francs, up from 1.3832; 5.6680 French francs, down from 5.6685; 1.8700 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8715; 1,241.20 Italian lire, up from 1,240.50; 1.2295 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2297 Japanese markets were closed for Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s birthday. The dollar was quoted 124.65 yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, fractionally down from 124.82 yen at the close of business in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Thursday. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of $ 449.75 dollars a troy ounce at midmorning, down from $ 451 late Thursday. A trader said buying interest began to wane in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Thursday as hopes faded that an oil-price stabilization pact would emerge from the meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was bid at $ 449.70, down from $ 452. Earlier, closed in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 451.17, down from $ 453.54. Silver bullion was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 6.47 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.50.
