<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced it was recalling nearly 26,000 1988-model cars to fix possible problems with a transmission cable that could cause false readings in the gear shift indicator. Included in the recall were about 17,500 <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regals </ORGANIZATION> and about 8,400 Pontiac Grand Prix models, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday in a written statement. Both models have potential problems with the transmission cable that could cause the cars to be in a gear other than that displayed on the shift indicator, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. Some Regals also may have a faulty stoplamp switch, which could make the brake lights inoperative when the brake pedal is depressed, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. In addition, the secondary hood latch of some of the cars may not engage properly, presenting the danger of the hood opening unexpectedly if the primary latch were to malfunction. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it was unaware of any accidents or injuries due to the potential problems. Owners were being notified to take the cars to dealers, who will make repairs at no cost.
