<HEAD>No Progress in Beef-Orange Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese officials have reported no progress after a third day of meetings to break a deadlock over lowering Japanese trade barriers against American beef and oranges. They agreed to meet again today, but no one on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation was optimistic about the outcome, said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, spokesman for the chief American negotiator, Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. The differences between the two sides `` have not been narrowed,'' said <PERSON> Hidero </PERSON> <PERSON> Maki </PERSON>, spokesman and economic affairs chief for Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s negotiator. The negotiations are going to take longer than anticipated, <PERSON> Maki </PERSON> told reporters Thursday. Adding to the gloom, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told a gathering of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> visitors, `` chances are not as bright as I'd like to see,'' that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will further open its market to beef and oranges. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> repeated warnings that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will try to have the Japanese import quotas declared illegal under the rules of <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had been requesting that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> end the quotas that the two countries agreed to in a four-year pact that expired at the end of March with the collapse of an earlier round of Sato-Yeutter negotiations. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said ending the quotas was still the demand. They declined to comment on Japanese reports that a compromise was under discussion. The talks have been centering on `` the timing of liberalization'' of imports into <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said Japanese Embassy spokesman <PERSON> Toshiyuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Takano </PERSON>. According to <PERSON> Maki </PERSON>, four specific topics are covered in the negotiations. They are: improvement of access to the Japanese market; future role of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Livestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, the semigovernment body that now handles 80 percent of beef imports; interim measures pending liberalization and measures to follow lifting of the quotas, he said.
