<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has tentatively agreed to operate the troubled <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear plant in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, company officials said. The deal is dependent on approval by <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> voters to restart the troubled facility, idled since an emergency shutdown in December 1985, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s chairman and chief executive officer. `` If the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> voters approve, we are confident that we can operate <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> in a safe and efficient manner,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said in announcing the agreement Thursday at the company's annual meeting in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>. `` Competition is increasing and the shackles of regulation seem to be loosening in some quarters,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> told shareholders. `` There is risk, but also great opportunity.'' Three of <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s seven nuclear units have the same <ORGANIZATION> Babcock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Wilcox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reactor design as the Rancho Seco plant. Details of the agreement in principle with the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> Municipal Utility District were not disclosed. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said operating <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, about 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, would enable the Charlotte-based utility to diversify and market its engineering and technical services _ and thus increase diversified earnings. A negotiating team headed by <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s president and chief operating officer, met for several hours Wednesday in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION>'s genera manager, and other <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> officials to discuss an operating arrangement, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> officials said. The plant currently is the object of two competing local initiatives on June 7 in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and one, offered by <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> and supported by <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, would authorize an 18-month test operating period. The other would close the plant permanently. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON>, one of <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION>'s five directors, attended <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting and accused <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> of interfering with <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION>'s internal affairs and `` meddling'' with the ballot measure. <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON> criticized <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> for contributing $ 100,000 to the campaign to keep the plant running and pleaded with shareholders: `` Please let us make that decision ourselves.'' In a subsequent interview, <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON> said, `` I do n't have a problem with <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> wanting to come out and run a plant efficiently. I do n't have a problem with <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> wanting to make some money in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>. My problem is the integrity of the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> political process.'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> abandoned its interest in owning the plant after it failed to find a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> partner. But <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, in an interview Thursday, said, `` We think we're doing what's in our interests and the interests of those consumers.'' `` The plant has n't run well,'' he conceded. `` But they have invested $ 1 billion in it. The incremental cost of running it, now that they've already got that investment, is very little and lower than any other source of electricity in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.''
