<HEAD>Judge Upholds USG's Poison Pill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ruled that <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can use a `` poison pill'' strategy in defending itself against <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>'s hostile $ 1.6 billion takeover bid. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holderman </PERSON> refused Thursday to grant a preliminary injunction sought by <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> against the use of the defensive tactic. USG's poison pill would make it prohibitively expensive for <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> to acquire an 85 percent stake in the company even if shareholders tendered the 39 million shares the Texas-based partnership is seeking. Under the plan, <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would have the right to buy a new series of preferred stock if suitors, like <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, acquire more than 20 percent of USG stock. <PERSON> Holderman </PERSON> said he based his decision on the corporate laws of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where many major companies are incorporated. `` Once the board decides to maintain the company's independence, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law does not require a board of directors to put their company on the auction block or assist a potential acquirer to formulate an adequate takeover bid,'' <PERSON> Holderman </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Day said he was pleased with the decision. <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, headed up by two <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilmen, says it has lined up financing commitments totaling $ 1.9 billion, including a $ 1.4 billion bank facility and $ 500 million in subordinated debt. Desert Partners has offered $ 42 a share in cash for up to 39 million USG shares. In addition, they would offer about $ 600 million in debt securities and warrants, or rights to buy stock, also valued at $ 42 each, for the balance of the deal. Desert Partners now owns 9.9 percent of <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> shares.
