<HEAD>Texas Railroad Commissioner Says OPEC Shows Interest In Visiting
Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s president is interested in either visiting <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or sending representatives to learn better ways of monitoring the cartel's oil production, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Railroad Commissioner <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> says. In a telephone interview Thursday with The <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said he met for about 90 minutes with <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> president and oil minister of <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. `` We discussed the monitoring procedures we use at the commission to know what everyone is producing,'' <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` He expressed interest in coming to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or at least sending some of his staff to see how we do that.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulates oil production in the state, which was devastated economically by a collapse in world oil prices two years ago. Alleged quota cheating by some members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> has been blamed for the current global oil glut and the weak prices. Members of the cartel have been meeting with non-member nations in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to discuss ways to stabilize prices. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> did not participate in the meetings, but came to hold private talks with participants. His presence received widespread attention and incited speculation of a possible strategic relationship between <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which would be the cartel's fourth-largest oil producer if it were a member Non-OPEC producers attending the meeting have suggested both <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and non-OPEC oil producers agree to 5 percent oil production cuts in order to boost prices. `` They've never really asked about <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> making cuts,'' <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said. `` But I told them we could not, would not consider making cuts because we consume more than we produce.'' Earlier this week, <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said he saw his mission as ` opening a dialogue'' with the cartel. `` We're not in love with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, but we need to have input'' into decisions by an organization that controls about 35 percent of the world's oil supplies, he said. `` I look at what's happened to our <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy'' since oil prices crashed in 1986, he said. `` No one else is going to be speaking up for the state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and someone had to do something.''
