<SECOND>AM-Britain-Securities, Bjt,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Firms Fail To Get Full Approval Under New Securities
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sweeping law to protect investors took effect Friday in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, but the new rules are so cumbersome that thousands of financial firms failed to get approval to stay in business and needed temporary reprieves. Widely criticized by the British securities industry, the government granted interim approval to about 7,000 firms until they could complete the complex paperwork and reporting requirements imposed by the law. About 30,000 other firms obtained approval prior to the deadline Friday, dubbed `` A Day,'' short for Appointed Day, the first day that key provisions of the Financial Services Act of 1986 were enforced. `` People are working very hard to get as many people through the hoop as quickly as possible,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dix </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for enforcing the new law. It was passed in response to the so-called `` Big Bang'' deregulation of October 1986, which liberalized <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s stodgy securities practices and was designed to make <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the world's leading financial center While the liberalization boosted <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s securities industry into a $ 43 billion-a-year business, lawmakers and consumer groups lobbied for the new law to guard against unethical practices that victimize investors. Under the new law, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> oversees five self-regulatory organizations responsible for policing the financial markets and enforcing provisions that ensure firms have enough capital to operate. Brokers and investment professionals operating without authorization face criminal sanctions ranging from fines to imprisonment. The new law also requires investment advisers to become more knowledgeable about client finances, investment goals and willingness to take risk. Many in the industry have complained that the new system is a hodge-podge of regulations that are difficult to understand, expensive to enforce and a threat to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s international attractiveness as a securities market. Some say the enforcement cost will run into the hundreds of millions of dollars and drive business elsewhere. `` We think that is a very real fear,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. He also claimed the law would not be as effective as many of its supporters believe. `` It is wrong to think that the new measures will prevent fraud and do what the politicians want, which is to catch crooks more quickly,'' <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said. But some consumer advocates claim the regulations do n't go far enough and fear the cost will be passed to investors. Some have complained because provisions for compensating customers who have lost money through the collapse of firms wo n't go into effect for months. `` What we're saying to investors is, ` Do n't be lulled into a sense of security,' `` said <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON>, a research manager at <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Under <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s financial deregulation, brokers were allowed to make markets in stocks, an activity previously restricted to firms called jobbers. The deregulation also abolished minimum commissions and allowed banks to enter the securities business. But less than two months afterward, several embarrasing securities scandals surfaced, inciting criticism that <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s financial district was not properly policed The biggest scandal by far has involved stock manipulation allegations surrounding brewery giant <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
