<HEAD>Japan and United States Clash at Regional Bank Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> called Friday for raising the <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s capital but faced opposition from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, in what appeared to be a struggle for influence over the financial institution. In a speech to 1,500 bankers and finance officials from 47 countries, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> Gov. <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said his country wants to recycle up to $ 30 billion in trade surplus funds. One way is by increasing its stock in the 21-year-old development bank, <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said. He said the bank, established to hasten economic development of poor <LOCATION> Asia-Pacific </LOCATION> countries, has to expand technical assistance to developing countries and increase loans not only to governments but also to private businesses to reduce poverty in the region. `` If <ORGANIZATION> ADB </ORGANIZATION> is to respond to these issues and to achieve growth, it is imperative that the bank's own financial base be strengthened, for it is upon this foundation that all operations rest,'' he said. `` And I believe that a general capital increase is urgently needed.'' The bank currently has an authorized capital of $ 22.8 billion. <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> told the annual meeting of the bank's board of governors that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> wants to increase its share in the bank's capital from 15 percent at present to at least 16.41 percent. `` And I hope the governors will give this request their favorable consideration,'' he added. But <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON>, deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, opposed any capital increase, saying, `` Financially, the bank remains in excellent shape.'' `` At this time, my government does not foresee agreement on a -LRB- general capital increase -RRB- before early 1990, and clearly our position on these negotiations will be much influenced by our perceptions of the bank's plans for using its resources,'' he said. Sources at the bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is trying to expand its influence over the bank by increasing its shareholdings and thus have the most votes at a time when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is faced with budgetary difficulties and cutting back on expenses. The bank, set up in 1966, is owned and controlled by the governments of 18 developed states and 29 developing Asian and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> countries. Policy is formulated by the board of governors, which meets every year and is composed of the 47 member-countries' finance ministers or central bank chiefs The bank's annual report for 1987 shows that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had a slight edge over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, controlling 15 percent of total shares and 12.4 percent of total voting power, against 14.7 percent and 12.2 percent for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
