<HEAD>Australian Tycoon Sells His Empire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court, whose fortune dwindled from billions to millions in October's market crash, sold most of his stake in his <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> business empire Friday. Two investor groups said they paid a total of 333 million Australian dollars, or about $ 253 million, for a nearly 40 percent interest in <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which has interests in a variety of industries. The sale reduced <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court's stake in <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which controls 43 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, to about 3 percent. The announcement ended days of speculation about the future of the once-feared corporate raider and also tolled the end of an era in Australian business. <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court, who at the peak of his success was one of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s wealthiest men, earning an estimated $ 43 every second, is reported to have become tired of corporate life, particularly in the wake of the stock market crash. The companies he controlled lost about $ 380 million, the biggest corporate loss in Australian history, due to investment writedowns in the wake of the global market collapse. Under the deal announced Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, a brewing and media magnate who won the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup in 1983, each purchased 19.9 percent stakes in <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The commission said it paid the equivalent of $ 1.90 a share for its stake, or about $ 122 million. <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, who made his purchase through <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, paid $ 2.05 a share, or about $ 131.5 million. Both parties said they regarded their holdings as investments only and noted that they did not collaborate in purchasing Bell shares. <ORGANIZATION> SGIC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Wyvern </PERSON> <PERSON> Rees </PERSON> said the government authority would not interfere with <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>'s management. <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court is expected to remain chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director Calling <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court's decision to sell most of his <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> holdings `` undoubtedly difficult,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was satisfied with its investment and had no plans to try to acquire the rest of the company. Since the market crash <ORGANIZATION> Holmes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> a </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has been selling assets to help ease his cash crunch. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> have sold off assets valued at about $ 3.42 billion. In November, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> sold <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s 12.3 percent stake in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil giant <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to takeover strategist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> for $ 795.5 million, taking an esimtated $ 96 million loss on the transaction. Earlier that month he also sold a 2.5 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Broken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Proprietary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s largest company, to other interests for nearly $ 200 million. He sold some of his properties in <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION> for about $ 140 million. <LOCATION> Broken </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, which has major interests in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and elsewhere, had been threatened in recent years by <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, which amassed an 11 percent stake in the company through several takeover bids. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> approved of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>'s asset sales so far but did not want the company to divest its <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> owns one of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s three commerical national television networks. Its stake in <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> could raise questions as to whether <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is in violation of the government's media cross-ownership laws, which limit the size of investments in television and newspaper concerns in the same city. Separately, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> a Court dropped his plan to merge <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGA