<HEAD>Northwest Parent, Pan Am Post First-Quarter Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reported losses for the first quarter which they blamed on higher costs. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, the eighth-largest airline, said its first quarter net loss narrowed to $ 83.3 million from $ 93.6 million a year earlier. Revenue jumped 18 percent, to $ 900.8 million from $ 763.1 million in the first three months of 1987. St. Paul-based <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, said it had a first quarter net loss of $ 43.5 million, widened from a loss of $ 35 million in the first three months of 1987. The loss occurred despite an increase in first-quarter revenue, to $ 1.24 billion from $ 1.17 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> said an improved performance by its Northeast shuttle service and <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> helped narrow its loss from a year earlier. The air shuttle links <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, while <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> provides ground services to other carriers in airports around the world. The company's main subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, posted an operating loss of $ 62 million in the first quarter, widened from a $ 51.1 million loss a year earlier. The deterioration was blamed on increases in the costs of fuel, advertising, aircraft rentals and other expenses. The loss at <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's fourth-largest airline, was attributed to rising costs and a strike threat by flight attendants. The company said its earnings also were affected by a $ 10 million one-time writedown of accounts receivable from a travel wholesaler. `` Higher fuel, payroll, travel agent commission and maintenance costs combined with the threat of a flight attendant strike contributed to the increased operating loss,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothmeier </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer. He said that compared with the first quarter of 1987, the price of fuel for the airline jumped by 7.3 cents a gallon to 59.2 cents, payroll expenses increased 7.4 percent to $ 407.8 million, and commissions paid to agents were up 22.1 percent to $ 192 million. Maintenance salaries and material expenses rose as the airline accelerated its overhaul of spare engines, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> said. The company reached a tentative contract agreement with its 6,700 flight attendants on March 22, averting a strike set for March 29. The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union local representing the attendants announced earlier Friday that the contract had been ratified through a mail-in vote. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> also said it was informed Friday by its flight attendants union that the attendants had voted to reject a new contract calling for $ 90 million in wage cuts and other labor concessions. The contract has been ratified by the unions representing pilots and flight engineers at the airline, and negotiations are ongoing between management and the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The company underwent a major management shakeup in January in which the chairman and other top executives were replaced. To ensure its financial recovery, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> would need labor concessions totaling around $ 540 million over three years, analysts and company sources estimate. The concessions agreed to by the pilots and flight engineers represent about $ 240 million over three years, while the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union has informally accepted $ 35 million.
