<HEAD>Voluntary Recall of 1988-Model 626, MX-6 for Throttle Defect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> announced a voluntary recall Friday of 1988-model 626 and MX-6 cars, saying a throttle defect may prevent the engine from slowing when the accelerator is released in cold weather. The recall covers all 1988-model 626 and MX-6 cars sold in the mainland <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but excludes cars sold in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON>. Of the 72,883 cars in the throttle recall, 42,810 of the 626 models are also being recalled to replace defective automatic shoulder belt mechanisms. There have been no reports of accidents or injuries caused by either problem, the company said. Cars should be returned to a <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> dealer. The throttle problem is caused by frost that may accumulate when the car is driven at highway speeds in cold weather. The accelerator pedal becomes hard to press, and when the driver takes his or her foot off the pedal, the engine continues to run at the same speed, <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said.
